INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-06-lesson-03','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Step 14: Analyse Token Supply and Step 22: Assess Regulatory Exposure','cmf-module-2-06','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Step 14: Analyse Token Supply and Step 22: Assess Regulatory Exposure, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Step 14: Analyse Token Supply

Review:

Circulating supply

Total supply

Maximum supply

Inflation rate

Minting authority

Burn mechanisms

Future issuance

Token unlock schedules

A low circulating supply can make a token appear scarce while large future allocations remain locked.

Compare current market capitalisation with fully diluted valuation.

A very large gap may indicate substantial future dilution.

Ask:

How quickly will supply grow?

Who receives the new tokens?

What might recipients do with them?

Can governance change the issuance rules?

Is the reported supply independently verifiable?

### Step 15: Examine Token Distribution

Investigate how the token was allocated.

Common allocations include:

Founders

Employees

Private investors

Public buyers

Community rewards

Ecosystem development

Treasury reserves

Warning signs may include:

Excessive insider ownership

Very low early-investor prices

Short vesting periods

Hidden allocations

A small public distribution

Large wallets capable of dominating governance

Token-distribution charts provided by a project should be compared with blockchain data and vesting documentation where possible.

### Step 16: Understand Value Capture

Value capture explains how project success could benefit the token.

Possible mechanisms include:

Users must pay fees in the token

Validators must stake it

Protocol fees are distributed to holders

Fees are used to buy or burn tokens

The token is required as collateral

Governance rights become economically important

Ask:

What causes demand for the token?

Is the demand recurring?

Who receives protocol fees?

Does the token provide a claim on revenue?

Does token supply grow faster than demand?

Can users access the product without holding it?

A popular network with weak token value capture can still produce disappointing investment results.

### Step 17: Review Revenue and Financial Sustainability

Projects require resources to continue operating.

Potential funding sources include:

Token sales

Venture investment

Protocol fees

Transaction fees

Commercial services

Treasury reserves

Grants

Evaluate:

Current revenue

Operating expenses

Treasury size

Treasury asset quality

Spending rate

Dependence on token sales

Expected financial runway

A project funded mainly by selling its own token may face difficulty during a bear market.

If token prices decline, more tokens must be sold to cover the same expenses, creating further selling pressure.

### Step 18: Analyse the Treasury

A project treasury may appear large because it contains substantial amounts of the project’s own token.

This valuation can be misleading.

If the project attempts to sell a large portion:

Liquidity may be insufficient

Price may decline

The treasury’s remaining value may fall

A stronger treasury may contain diversified and liquid assets.

Also examine governance:

Who controls the treasury?

Are transactions transparent?

Is spending approved publicly?

Are several signatures required?

Has money been used responsibly?

Treasury size matters, but governance and liquidity matter equally.

### Step 19: Evaluate Competition

Identify both blockchain and traditional alternatives.

A project may compete with:

Other blockchain networks

Centralised financial services

Payment companies

Cloud-computing providers

Traditional databases

Existing digital marketplaces

Compare:

Security

Speed

Cost

Decentralisation

User experience

Liquidity

Brand trust

Developer support

Regulatory position

Network effects

Avoid assuming that better technology guarantees victory.

Markets often reward distribution, simplicity, trust and existing adoption.

### Step 20: Assess Network Effects and Defensibility

A project has defensibility when competitors cannot easily copy or replace its advantages.

Potential advantages include:

Large developer ecosystem

Deep liquidity

Strong brand

Established security record

Integrated applications

Proprietary technology

Regulatory licences

Active user community

Ask:

Why would users remain?

What prevents applications from moving elsewhere?

How costly is switching?

Does each new user make the network more valuable?

Can a competitor reproduce the same product quickly?

A project with no defensible advantage may struggle even if its initial idea is useful.

### Step 21: Examine Governance and Control

Governance determines who can change the system.

Investigate:

Who proposes upgrades?

Who votes?

How is voting power calculated?

Who controls administrative keys?

Can transactions be frozen?

Can new tokens be minted?

Can smart contracts be upgraded?

Who controls emergency functions?

A project may use decentralised language while retaining substantial central control.

Central control is not automatically unacceptable. It may support rapid development or emergency response.

The important requirement is transparency.

Users should know where authority exists and how it may affect them.

### Step 22: Assess Regulatory Exposure

Consider whether the project involves:

Investment promises

Stablecoins

Lending

Derivatives

Privacy tools

Tokenised securities

Custody

Payments

Gambling-like applications

These activities may attract different legal requirements.

Ask:

Where does the team operate?

Which users are targeted?

Has the project restricted certain regions?

Does the token resemble an investment contract?

Could exchanges be required to delist it?

Does the project rely on one legal interpretation?

Regulatory uncertainty can affect access, liquidity and adoption even when the technology continues functioning.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',3,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
