INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-14-lesson-06','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Common Misunderstandings and Key Takeaway','cmf-module-2-14','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Common Misunderstandings and Key Takeaway, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Common Misunderstandings

#### “More Tokens Mean More Diversification”

Many tokens may share the same market and technology risks.

#### “Core Cryptocurrency Assets Are Safe”

They may be more established but remain volatile and uncertain.

#### “A Stablecoin Allocation Removes Risk”

It replaces price volatility with issuer, reserve, liquidity and regulatory risks.

#### “Equal Weighting Treats Every Asset Fairly”

Equal capital amounts can create very unequal risk exposures.

#### “Rebalancing Always Means Selling Winners and Buying Losers”

Fundamentals must be reviewed before restoring an allocation.

#### “A Long Time Horizon Allows Unlimited Risk”

Time cannot repair fraud, insolvency or permanent project failure.

#### “Small Positions Do Not Need Research”

Several small speculative holdings can combine into a large risky exposure.

#### “Holding Several Exchanges Diversifies Market Risk”

It may reduce custody concentration but does not diversify the underlying asset prices.

#### “A Portfolio That Performed Well Was Well Constructed”

A poorly designed portfolio can succeed temporarily during favourable conditions.

### Module Summary

Cryptocurrency portfolio construction is the process of deciding:

Which assets to hold

What role each asset performs

How much capital to allocate

How risks interact

How the portfolio will be monitored and rebalanced

The portfolio should begin with a clear objective, time horizon and assessment of risk capacity.

Position sizing is a primary risk-management tool.

Diversification should focus on different sources of risk rather than merely increasing the number of token names.

A portfolio should account for:

Market risk

Correlation

Liquidity

Tokenomics

Custody

Platform exposure

Stablecoin risk

Smart contract risk

Leverage

Core-and-satellite structures, maximum position limits and liquidity reserves can provide useful organisational frameworks.

Every holding should have a written thesis and defined invalidation conditions.

Rebalancing restores intended risk levels but should be combined with updated fundamental analysis.

A well-constructed portfolio does not eliminate losses. It limits the ability of one failed assumption, asset or platform to cause unacceptable harm.

### Key Takeaway

A cryptocurrency portfolio should not be a collection of exciting tokens.

It should be a deliberate system in which every asset has a role, every position has a limit and every major risk has been considered.

You cannot control what markets will do.

You can control how much you expose, how widely the risk is distributed and whether one mistake has the power to destroy the entire portfolio.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,3,0,0,0,'','',6,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
