INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-25-lesson-05','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Limit Orders on a DEX and Fake DEX Interfaces','cmf-module-2-25','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Limit Orders on a DEX and Fake DEX Interfaces, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Limit Orders on a DEX

Some DEXs support limit orders.

A user specifies the price at which they are willing to trade.

Potential benefits include:

Greater price control

Reduced need to monitor continuously

Avoidance of immediate market impact

Potential limitations include:

The order may never fill

Partial execution may occur

Network fees may apply

The execution mechanism may rely on third-party keepers

The market may move away before confirmation

A limit order manages price, not the quality or legitimacy of the token.

### Stop and Conditional Orders

More advanced decentralised trading protocols may support:

Stop-loss orders

Take-profit orders

Trailing stops

Trigger-based swaps

Perpetual futures orders

These functions may rely on:

Oracles

Automation networks

Keepers

Off-chain triggers

Smart contracts

A conditional order is only as reliable as the entire execution system.

During extreme volatility, the final price may differ substantially from the trigger price.

### Token Contract Addresses

Token names and symbols are not unique.

Anyone may create a token using:

The name of a legitimate project

A similar ticker symbol

A copied logo

False branding

The token contract address is the primary technical identifier.

Before swapping, confirm the address using reliable sources such as:

The project’s official documentation

A reputable blockchain explorer

A trusted token list

Several verified official channels

Do not rely only on:

Token name

Logo

Search-engine advertisement

Social-media message

A link sent by a stranger

Buying the wrong token is usually irreversible.

### Counterfeit Tokens

A counterfeit token may imitate a legitimate asset.

Possible warning signs include:

Very low liquidity

Recently created contract

No verified official link

Unusual transfer behaviour

A large supply held by one wallet

Missing or copied documentation

Inconsistent contract addresses

The DEX may display the token because its markets are permissionless.

Appearance on the platform is not endorsement.

### Honeypot Tokens

A honeypot token allows users to buy but prevents or severely restricts selling.

The contract may contain malicious rules such as:

Only selected addresses may sell

Extremely high selling taxes

Blacklisting functions

Transfer restrictions

Hidden administrator controls

The rising price can attract buyers because purchases occur while selling remains impossible.

Before trading an unfamiliar token, examine:

Contract code

Buy and sell simulations

Existing successful sell transactions

Holder distribution

Administrator permissions

Independent security analysis

Automated scanners can help but may also fail to detect sophisticated contracts.

### Transfer Taxes

Some token contracts charge fees when tokens are transferred, bought or sold.

The fee may support:

Treasury funding

Token burning

Holder rewards

Marketing

Liquidity

It may also be abusive.

A token may impose:

A moderate disclosed tax

A changeable tax

A very high selling tax

A one-hundred-percent tax preventing exit

DEX quotes may not always reflect unusual transfer mechanics correctly.

Users should understand the contract before increasing slippage to compensate.

### Token Blacklists and Pausing

A token contract may permit administrators to:

Freeze addresses

Pause transfers

Change fees

Restrict trading

Mint additional tokens

Exclude selected wallets from restrictions

These functions may exist for regulatory or emergency reasons.

They may also enable abuse.

The user should determine:

Which powers exist

Who controls them

Whether they are limited

Whether ownership has been transferred or renounced

Whether renunciation claims are genuine and relevant

A permissionless DEX cannot override restrictions coded into the token itself.

### Malicious Approvals

A fraudulent application may ask the user to approve a valuable token unrelated to the supposed transaction.

Once approved, the attacker may transfer the token from the wallet.

Warning signs include:

Approval requests for unexpected assets

Unlimited permissions

Unfamiliar contract addresses

Urgent claims or migrations

Requests to “verify” the wallet

Transactions with unreadable or unexplained data

The wallet prompt should be reviewed before every approval.

### Signature-Based Attacks

Not every malicious action appears as an ordinary token transfer.

A user may sign a message that authorises:

A marketplace listing

A token permit

An asset transfer

An order

A broader delegated permission

The signature itself may not require a network fee, making it appear harmless.

Users should avoid signing messages they do not understand.

A gas-free signature can still carry serious financial authority.

### Fake DEX Interfaces

Attackers may create counterfeit copies of well-known DEX websites.

The interface may look almost identical to the legitimate platform.

The fraudulent site may:

Request malicious approvals

Replace destination addresses

Display fake balances

Ask for a seed phrase

Redirect to malicious contracts

Safer practices include:

Using a verified bookmark

Checking the domain character by character

Avoiding sponsored search links

Confirming official links through several sources

Using a separate low-value wallet for experimentation','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',5,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-25-lesson-06','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Domain and Front-End Risk and Stablecoin Risk on DEXs','cmf-module-2-25','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Domain and Front-End Risk and Stablecoin Risk on DEXs, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Domain and Front-End Risk

Even a legitimate DEX domain or interface may be compromised.

Possible causes include:

Domain hijacking

Website-code compromise

Malicious software updates

Front-end developer attacks

Compromised analytics or third-party scripts

The underlying smart contracts may remain secure while the interface directs users toward malicious transactions.

Experienced users may verify contract addresses and transaction details independently.

Most users should pause activity when the protocol reports front-end concerns.

### Smart Contract Risk

DEX contracts can be exploited through:

Coding errors

Re-entrancy

Incorrect access controls

Arithmetic problems

Upgrade vulnerabilities

Economic attacks

Oracle manipulation

Integration failures

A mature DEX with substantial operating history may have lower relative risk than an unaudited new protocol.

It still cannot be considered risk-free.

Users may be exposed to the DEX contract only during a swap or for a longer period through token approvals and liquidity positions.

### Upgradeable Contracts

Some DEX contracts can be upgraded after deployment.

Upgradeable designs allow developers to:

Fix vulnerabilities

Add features

Improve efficiency

Respond to network changes

They also create risks:

Malicious upgrades

Compromised administrator keys

Governance capture

Unexpected rule changes

User inability to exit before implementation

Review:

Who controls upgrades

Whether a multisignature is used

Whether a timelock exists

Whether changes are announced publicly

### Emergency Controls

A DEX may include powers to:

Pause trading

Disable a pool

Block a token

Restrict withdrawals

Change fees

Redirect protocol functions

These powers can protect users during an exploit.

They also demonstrate that operational control remains concentrated.

The existence of emergency controls is not automatically negative.

The important questions concern transparency, limits and who holds the authority.

### Liquidity Risk

A DEX market may appear active but contain limited actual liquidity.

Low liquidity increases:

Price impact

Slippage

Manipulation risk

Volatility

Difficulty exiting

Liquidity can disappear if:

Providers withdraw

Incentives end

A token loses value

A smart contract concern emerges

The paired asset depegs

Users should review the specific pool, not only the DEX’s total liquidity.

### Rug Pulls and Liquidity Removal

A rug pull may occur when project creators or major liquidity providers withdraw valuable assets from a trading pool.

Token holders may then be unable to sell except at extremely low prices.

A liquidity lock may reduce immediate withdrawal risk.

However, verify:

Which pool is locked

How much liquidity is locked

When the lock expires

Whether the team can create another pool

Whether token minting remains possible

Whether the paired asset has genuine value

Locked liquidity does not prove that the token or project is legitimate.

### Pool Imbalance

A liquidity pool may become heavily imbalanced when traders prefer one asset over another.

In a stablecoin pool, this may indicate that participants are selling a stablecoin they no longer trust.

The pool may become filled with the weaker asset while the stronger assets are removed.

A favourable exchange rate can therefore be a warning rather than an opportunity.

Users should investigate why a pool has become imbalanced before trading against it.

### Oracle Risk on Advanced DEXs

Simple AMMs derive prices from their internal asset balances.

More advanced DEXs and derivative platforms may use external price oracles.

Oracle failure can cause:

Incorrect trade execution

Invalid liquidations

Mispriced collateral

Protocol losses

Unfair settlement

The DEX’s design should explain:

Which oracle is used

How often prices update

How manipulation is prevented

What happens when data becomes unavailable

### Bridge and Wrapped-Asset Risk

A DEX may trade assets that were bridged from another blockchain.

The wrapped token depends on:

Bridge security

Custody

Validator or signer integrity

Redemption

Backing reserves

A bridged token can lose value relative to the original asset if the bridge is compromised or withdrawals become unavailable.

The DEX may continue quoting the token even when its backing is uncertain.

Confirm whether the asset is native, wrapped or bridged.

### Fake or Weak Wrapped Assets

Several wrapped versions of the same asset may exist.

They may differ in:

Issuer

Bridge

Custody

Liquidity

Redemption rights

Security

A token symbol may not clearly communicate these differences.

Always verify the exact contract and backing mechanism.

A cheaper wrapped token may be cheaper because market participants doubt its redeemability.

### Stablecoin Risk on DEXs

Stablecoins are frequently used as DEX quote assets.

If a stablecoin depegs:

Token prices quoted in it may appear distorted

Liquidity pools may become imbalanced

Arbitrage may accelerate

Traders may receive the weaker asset

Collateral values may change

A trade that appears profitable in stablecoin terms may lose value against national currency or another stable asset.

Check both assets in the trading pair.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',6,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-25-lesson-07','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Decentralised Perpetual Exchanges and Why a Test Sale Matters','cmf-module-2-25','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Decentralised Perpetual Exchanges and Why a Test Sale Matters, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Decentralised Perpetual Exchanges

Some DEXs offer leveraged perpetual futures rather than simple token swaps.

They may use:

Liquidity pools

Order books

Oracles

Collateral vaults

Funding rates

Liquidation engines

These products introduce additional risks:

Leverage

Liquidation

Funding costs

Oracle failure

Smart contract risk

Liquidity imbalance

Counterparty or pool losses

A decentralised interface does not make leveraged trading less dangerous.

### Governance and DEX Fees

A DEX may issue a governance token that allows holders to vote on:

Trading fees

Treasury spending

Incentive programmes

Supported chains

Contract upgrades

Revenue distribution

The governance token does not automatically receive the DEX’s revenue.

Investigate:

Which fees exist

Who receives them

Whether token holders have an enforceable claim

Whether governance can change the distribution

How concentrated voting power is

High DEX volume does not automatically create value for the governance token.

### DEX Volume

DEX volume measures the value of trades executed through the protocol.

High volume may indicate:

Strong usage

Market volatility

Incentive-driven activity

Arbitrage

Wash trading

Liquidations

Volume should be considered alongside:

Protocol fees

Active users

Liquidity

Retention

Incentive costs

Token value capture

High activity can be genuine without making the protocol profitable or its token attractive.

### DEX Total Value Locked

A DEX’s total value locked may include assets deposited in:

Liquidity pools

Trading vaults

Collateral systems

Staking contracts

TVL can indicate available capital, but it may be influenced by:

Token-price appreciation

Temporary incentives

Double counting

Concentrated liquidity

The protocol’s own token

TVL should not be used as a complete measure of security, liquidity or project value.

### User Privacy

A DEX may not require a conventional user account.

This does not make transactions private.

Public blockchain activity can reveal:

Wallet balances

Trading history

Protocol interactions

Linked addresses

Timing and size of positions

Centralised exchanges, analytics companies and other parties may connect wallet addresses with real identities.

Users should treat DeFi activity as potentially permanent and traceable.

### Regulatory Restrictions

A DEX protocol may be technically accessible from many locations.

The user may still be subject to laws relating to:

Taxation

Securities

Sanctions

Derivatives

Money laundering

Consumer protection

Exchange controls

Front-end operators may restrict users in particular jurisdictions.

Access through a wallet does not determine whether the activity is legally permitted.

Users should understand the rules applicable to them.

### DEX Record-Keeping

DEX transactions may create reporting or tax obligations.

Records should include:

Date and time

Wallet address

Transaction identifier

Asset sold

Asset received

Quantities

Market values

DEX and network fees

Cost basis

Contract addresses

Blockchain records provide evidence but may not calculate tax treatment automatically.

Complex routing can make record-keeping difficult because one visible swap may involve several intermediary trades.

### Evaluating a Decentralised Exchange

A DEX assessment can examine several areas.

### Operating History

How long has it operated?

Has it survived volatile markets?

Has it previously been exploited?

### Smart Contracts

Is the code public?

Are contracts verified?

Can they be upgraded?

### Security

Have audits been published?

Is there a bug bounty?

How were previous incidents handled?

### Governance

Who controls upgrades and emergency powers?

Is voting power concentrated?

### Liquidity

How deep are the relevant pools?

Is liquidity dependent on incentives?

### Trading Quality

What are the fees, spreads, price impact and slippage?

Does the DEX provide MEV protection?

### Front End

Is the official interface easy to verify?

Can the contracts be accessed if the website fails?

### Token Support

How are token warnings and lists managed?

Does the platform clearly distinguish unverified assets?

### Safer DEX Trading Process



### Step 1: Verify the Official Interface

Use reliable official sources and a saved bookmark.

### Step 2: Confirm the Blockchain Network

Ensure the wallet and DEX are using the intended network.

### Step 3: Verify Both Token Contracts

Confirm the exact contract addresses independently.

### Step 4: Review Liquidity

Examine pool depth, expected price impact and recent activity.

### Step 5: Check the Token Contract

Look for:

Sell restrictions

Transfer taxes

Blacklisting

Minting powers

Administrator controls

### Step 6: Use an Appropriate Wallet

Avoid connecting a long-term storage wallet to unfamiliar applications.

### Step 7: Review the Approval

Approve only the necessary token and amount where practical.

### Step 8: Review the Quote

Check:

Expected output

Minimum received

Fees

Slippage

Price impact

Route

### Step 9: Test With a Small Trade

Confirm that the token can be bought, displayed and sold.

### Step 10: Verify the Transaction

Use a blockchain explorer to confirm the result.

### Step 11: Revoke Unnecessary Permissions

Remove approvals that are no longer needed.

### Step 12: Maintain Records

Store transaction information without recording private keys or seed phrases.

### Why a Test Sale Matters

A small purchase confirms only that buying is possible.

A test sale may help reveal:

Honeypot restrictions

Unexpected selling taxes

Low exit liquidity

Transfer errors

Incorrect token contracts

A successful test sale does not guarantee future liquidity or safety.

The contract may contain changeable rules, and administrators may alter restrictions later.

Nevertheless, testing both directions can expose obvious problems before a larger position is created.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',7,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-25-lesson-08','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Separate Wallet Strategy and Module Summary','cmf-module-2-25','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Separate Wallet Strategy and Module Summary, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Separate Wallet Strategy

A user may separate wallets according to purpose.

### Long-Term Wallet

Used for assets that rarely interact with smart contracts.

### Established DeFi Wallet

Used with researched protocols.

### Experimental Wallet

Contains limited funds and interacts with unfamiliar applications.

This structure can reduce the value exposed through one malicious approval.

It also creates additional recovery and record-keeping responsibilities.

Every wallet must be backed up securely.

### DEX Transaction Checklist

Before confirming a swap, ask:

Am I using the official DEX interface?

Is the website address correct?

Is the wallet connected to the correct network?

Have I verified both token contract addresses?

Is the token genuine?

Can the token be sold?

Does the contract contain transfer taxes or restrictions?

How much liquidity exists in the specific pool?

What is the expected price impact?

What is the slippage tolerance?

What is the minimum amount received?

What protocol fee applies?

What network fee applies?

Is the route direct or routed through other tokens and protocols?

Does the route use bridged or wrapped assets?

What approval is being requested?

Is the approval limited or unlimited?

Am I signing a transaction or a broader message permission?

Could the trade be vulnerable to a sandwich attack?

Is protected routing available?

Is the position size appropriate for the liquidity?

Have I tested the process with a small amount?

Can I record the transaction accurately?

What will I do if the website becomes unavailable?

### Common DEX Mistakes



### Buying by Token Name Alone

The user purchases a counterfeit token with the same name or symbol.

### Using a Fake Interface

A copied website requests malicious approvals or signatures.

### Ignoring Price Impact

A large order receives far fewer tokens than expected.

### Setting Excessive Slippage

The transaction becomes vulnerable to poor execution and sandwich attacks.

### Approving Unlimited Spending Carelessly

A compromised contract retains authority over valuable assets.

### Assuming Every Listed Token Is Verified

Permissionless markets allow fraudulent tokens to trade.

### Trading Without Testing a Sale

The user discovers only later that the token contains restrictive contract logic.

### Ignoring Network Fees

A small trade becomes unprofitable after approvals and transaction costs.

### Using a Long-Term Storage Wallet

A high-value wallet is exposed to unnecessary smart contract risk.

### Confusing Wrapped and Native Assets

The user accepts additional bridge or issuer risk unintentionally.

### Treating TVL as Guaranteed Liquidity

The relevant pool may still be shallow or inactive near the current price.

### Ignoring Tax Records

Complex swaps become difficult to reconstruct later.

### Common Misunderstandings

#### “A DEX Has No Intermediaries”

It still depends on smart contracts, validators, front ends, liquidity providers, routers and sometimes administrators.

#### “A Token on a DEX Has Been Approved”

Permissionless listing means anyone may create a market.

#### “Self-Custody Means the Trade Is Safe”

The user may still approve a malicious contract or purchase a fraudulent token.

#### “The Displayed Price Is the Price I Will Receive”

Price impact, slippage and fees change the final result.

#### “High Slippage Helps the Trade Work Better”

It improves execution probability while allowing a worse price.

#### “Unlimited Approval Is the Same as a Token Transfer”

Approval grants future spending authority; the tokens may be taken later if the contract is compromised.

#### “A Gas-Free Signature Cannot Move Assets”

Some signatures authorise later transfers or orders.

#### “Large TVL Means Every Pool Is Liquid”

Liquidity may be concentrated in other assets or price ranges.

#### “Locked Liquidity Prevents Every Rug Pull”

Minting, taxes, insider selling and malicious contract controls may remain.

#### “A Successful Purchase Proves the Token Is Legitimate”

Honeypot tokens are specifically designed to allow buying while restricting selling.

#### “A Decentralised Exchange Is Outside Regulation”

Users, developers and front-end operators may still have legal obligations.

#### “DEX Trading Is Anonymous”

Public blockchain transactions are traceable and may be linked to real identities.

### Module Summary

A decentralised exchange enables users to trade digital assets through blockchain smart contracts.

DEX models include:

Automated market makers

On-chain order books

Off-chain matching with on-chain settlement

Hybrid exchanges

Aggregators

Automated market makers use liquidity pools and mathematical pricing rules.

As a trade changes the pool’s asset balances, the exchange rate changes.

This creates price impact.

Slippage describes the difference between expected and actual execution.

DEX aggregators may divide trades across several pools to improve pricing, but they introduce additional contract and routing dependencies.

DEX users must manage:

Wallet security

Token approvals

Network fees

Contract verification

Slippage

Liquidity

Transaction ordering

Record-keeping

Important risks include:

Counterfeit tokens

Honeypots

Transfer taxes

Malicious signatures

Fake interfaces

Smart contract exploits

Liquidity removal

MEV and sandwich attacks

Wrapped-asset and bridge failure

Stablecoin depegging

A token’s presence on a DEX is not an endorsement.

Before trading, verify the exact contract address, inspect liquidity and token permissions, review every wallet request and test the transaction with a small amount.

A DEX gives the user direct market access.

It also gives the user direct responsibility for confirming what is being traded, which contract is being authorised and whether an exit will remain possible.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',8,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
