INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-28-lesson-01','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','What Is Cryptocurrency Lending? and Lending Pools','cmf-module-2-28','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in What Is Cryptocurrency Lending? and Lending Pools, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Learning Objectives

By the end of this module, you should be able to:

Explain how cryptocurrency lending and borrowing protocols operate

Distinguish between centralised lending and decentralised lending

Understand why most DeFi loans are overcollateralised

Calculate loan-to-value and collateral ratios

Explain collateral factors, liquidation thresholds and health factors

Understand how lending and borrowing interest rates are determined

Distinguish between supply yield, borrowing cost and protocol incentives

Explain how liquidations protect a lending protocol

Identify the risks of recursive borrowing and leveraged lending strategies

Understand how oracles, liquidity and stablecoins affect lending markets

Evaluate lender, borrower and protocol-level risks

Assess a lending protocol using a structured framework

Participate more cautiously in cryptocurrency credit markets

### Introduction

Lending and borrowing are central functions of the financial system.

Traditional lenders evaluate borrowers using information such as:

Income

Employment

Credit history

Existing debt

Assets

Legal identity

Ability to repay

Cryptocurrency lending can operate differently.

A blockchain protocol may allow a user to deposit digital assets as collateral and borrow another asset without submitting a conventional credit application.

The smart contract does not necessarily know:

Who the borrower is

Where the borrower lives

Whether the borrower is employed

What the borrower earns

Whether the borrower intends to repay

Instead, the protocol protects lenders by requiring collateral worth more than the amount borrowed.

If the collateral falls too far in value, the protocol may sell it automatically.

This makes permissionless borrowing possible, but it introduces new risks involving:

Volatile collateral

Smart contracts

Price oracles

Liquidations

Stablecoins

Market liquidity

Governance

Network congestion

Lenders may earn interest, but they are not receiving a risk-free return.

Borrowers gain liquidity, but they can lose their collateral during ordinary market volatility.

A complete analysis must examine the economics of the loan, the assets involved and the mechanism used to protect the protocol.

### What Is Cryptocurrency Lending?

Cryptocurrency lending allows one party to make digital assets available to another party in return for interest or another form of compensation.

The main participants may include:

Lenders or suppliers

Borrowers

A centralised company

A decentralised protocol

Collateral providers

Liquidators

Governance participants

Price-oracle providers

The lender may supply:

Stablecoins

Native blockchain assets

Tokenised assets

Other accepted cryptocurrencies

The borrower may use the borrowed funds for:

Trading

Liquidity

Business activity

Tax planning

Hedging

DeFi strategies

Avoiding the immediate sale of an existing asset

The economic purpose resembles conventional credit, but the operating structure can be very different.

### Centralised Cryptocurrency Lending

A centralised lending platform is operated by a company.

Users may deposit assets with the company and receive interest.

The company may lend those assets to:

Institutional traders

Market makers

Hedge funds

Retail borrowers

Other platforms

Affiliated businesses

The company decides:

Who may borrow

Which collateral is accepted

Which interest rate applies

How customer assets are used

When withdrawals are processed

Users depend on the company’s:

Solvency

Risk management

Security

Accounting

Legal structure

Honesty

The platform may describe the product as an earn account, savings product or staking service even when the underlying activity is lending.

### Centralised Lending Risks

Potential risks include:

Platform insolvency

Borrower default

Unsecured lending

Fraud

Poor collateral management

Rehypothecation

Withdrawal suspension

Regulatory intervention

Cybersecurity breaches

Lack of transparent reserves

A user may see only an account balance and interest payment.

They may not know:

Who borrowed the assets

Whether collateral exists

Whether the collateral is liquid

Whether the company has lent the same assets several times

Whether customer deposits are legally protected

Convenience can hide substantial counterparty risk.

### Decentralised Lending

A decentralised lending protocol uses smart contracts to manage deposits, loans, interest and liquidations.

A simplified process may be:

Lenders deposit assets into a smart contract

Borrowers deposit approved collateral

The protocol calculates a borrowing limit

Borrowers withdraw available assets

Interest accrues automatically

Oracles monitor collateral values

Borrowers repay their debt

The collateral becomes withdrawable

Undercollateralised positions may be liquidated

The rules are generally visible in the protocol code and documentation.

Users interact through blockchain wallets.

No traditional loan officer may be involved.

### Lending Pools

Many DeFi protocols use pooled lending.

Lenders deposit assets into shared liquidity pools.

Borrowers draw from those pools.

For example, a stablecoin market may contain:

Ten million units supplied

Six million units borrowed

Four million units available for withdrawal or new loans

Interest paid by borrowers is distributed among suppliers after protocol fees and other deductions.

The individual lender is not necessarily matched with one specific borrower.

They hold a proportional claim on the shared pool.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',1,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-28-lesson-02','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Supply Tokens and Health Factor','cmf-module-2-28','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Supply Tokens and Health Factor, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Supply Tokens

When a lender deposits an asset, the protocol may issue a receipt token representing the position.

The receipt token may:

Increase in quantity as interest accrues

Increase in redemption value

Represent a claim on supplied assets

Be transferable

Be usable as collateral

Be deposited into another protocol

The receipt token creates composability.

It also adds risk.

If it is used elsewhere, the lender becomes exposed to:

The original lending protocol

The receipt token

The second protocol

Any additional borrowing or liquidity strategy

A deposited asset can therefore become part of several interconnected positions.

### Why Borrow Cryptocurrency?

A borrower may want liquidity without selling an existing asset.

Suppose an investor owns a cryptocurrency expected to appreciate over the long term.

Selling it may:

End future exposure

Create a taxable event

Conflict with the investment thesis

Be undesirable during a temporary price decline

The investor may instead deposit it as collateral and borrow a stablecoin.

This preserves exposure to the collateral asset while creating spendable or investable liquidity.

However, the borrower now has:

Continued asset-price risk

Debt

Interest expense

Liquidation risk

Smart contract exposure

Borrowing does not remove the need to sell. It may postpone or force a sale under less favourable conditions.

### Why Most DeFi Loans Are Overcollateralised

A permissionless lending protocol may not have access to conventional borrower information.

It cannot depend easily on:

Salary deductions

Credit bureaux

Court enforcement

Personal guarantees

Property registration

Collection agencies

It therefore requires collateral worth more than the loan.

Suppose a borrower wants 10,000 stablecoin units.

The protocol may require collateral worth 15,000 or 20,000 units.

If the collateral value falls, the protocol can liquidate it before the loan becomes undersecured.

Overcollateralisation replaces much of the conventional credit assessment with automated asset protection.

### Collateral

Collateral is an asset pledged to secure a loan.

Accepted collateral may include:

Native blockchain coins

Stablecoins

Liquid-staking tokens

Wrapped assets

Tokenised real-world assets

Governance tokens

Liquidity-provider positions

Each collateral asset has different risks.

A protocol should consider:

Price volatility

Liquidity

Market depth

Oracle quality

Token concentration

Smart contract risk

Bridge risk

Stablecoin risk

A volatile or illiquid asset normally supports less borrowing than a stable and liquid one.

### Loan-to-Value Ratio

The loan-to-value ratio, or LTV, compares the amount borrowed with the value of the collateral.

The formula is:

LTV = Loan value ÷ Collateral value × 100

Suppose:

Collateral value: 20,000 units

Debt: 10,000 units

The LTV is:

10,000 ÷ 20,000 × 100 = 50 percent

A lower LTV generally means a greater safety buffer.

A higher LTV means the position is closer to liquidation.

### Collateral Ratio

The collateral ratio expresses the relationship in the opposite direction.

The formula is:

Collateral ratio = Collateral value ÷ Debt value × 100

Using the same example:

20,000 ÷ 10,000 × 100 = 200 percent

An LTV of fifty percent is equivalent to a collateral ratio of two hundred percent.

Both measurements describe the same position from different perspectives.

Users should confirm which measure a protocol displays.

### Collateral Factor

A collateral factor determines how much borrowing capacity an asset provides.

Suppose a protocol assigns an asset a collateral factor of seventy percent.

If a user deposits collateral worth 10,000 units, the theoretical maximum borrowing capacity may be:

10,000 × 70 percent = 7,000 units

The collateral factor reflects the protocol’s assessment of the asset’s risk.

A more volatile or less liquid asset may receive a lower factor.

A stable and liquid asset may receive a higher one.

The maximum permitted amount is not necessarily a prudent borrowing amount.

Borrowing to the limit leaves little room for market movement.

### Liquidation Threshold

The liquidation threshold is the point at which a borrower’s position becomes eligible for liquidation.

It may differ from the initial borrowing limit.

For example:

Maximum initial LTV: 70 percent

Liquidation threshold: 80 percent

A user depositing collateral worth 10,000 units may initially borrow up to 7,000.

If the debt rises or collateral falls until the LTV reaches eighty percent, liquidation can begin.

The difference between the initial borrowing limit and liquidation threshold creates a limited safety buffer.

### Health Factor

Many protocols display a health factor to summarise the safety of a borrowing position.

A simplified formula may be expressed as:

Health factor = Adjusted collateral value ÷ Debt value

Adjusted collateral value usually incorporates the liquidation threshold.

A health factor:

Above 1 indicates the position is currently above the liquidation boundary

Equal to 1 indicates liquidation eligibility

Below 1 indicates an undercollateralised position

Exact formulas differ between protocols.

A health factor slightly above one may still be dangerously close to liquidation.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',2,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-28-lesson-03','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Health Factor Example and Supply APR and APY','cmf-module-2-28','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Health Factor Example and Supply APR and APY, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Health Factor Example

Suppose:

Collateral value: 15,000 units

Liquidation threshold: 80 percent

Debt: 10,000 units

Adjusted collateral value:

15,000 × 80 percent = 12,000 units

Health factor:

12,000 ÷ 10,000 = 1.20

The position has a health factor of 1.20.

If the collateral falls to 12,500:

Adjusted collateral value:

12,500 × 80 percent = 10,000

Health factor:

10,000 ÷ 10,000 = 1.00

The position may now be liquidated.

### Maximum Borrowing Is Not Safe Borrowing

Protocols often display the maximum amount a user is technically allowed to borrow.

This limit protects the protocol under its model.

It does not guarantee that the borrower can tolerate normal volatility.

Borrowing near the maximum can create:

Frequent liquidation risk

Constant monitoring requirements

High emotional pressure

Inability to respond during network congestion

Forced selling after a modest decline

A prudent borrower generally maintains a larger buffer than the minimum protocol requirement.

### Interest Accrual

Borrowing interest typically accrues continuously or at frequent intervals.

The debt may increase every block or over another protocol-defined period.

Suppose a borrower owes 10,000 units at an annualised rate of ten percent.

If the rate remained constant for one year, the approximate simple interest would be:

10,000 × 10 percent = 1,000 units

The borrower would owe approximately:

11,000 units

In practice:

Rates may change

Interest may compound

Fees may apply

Repayments may occur earlier

The debt token may update continuously

A borrowing position can move toward liquidation even when the collateral price remains unchanged because the debt balance is growing.

### Supply Interest

Lenders earn a portion of the interest paid by borrowers.

Suppose:

Borrowers pay an average rate of eight percent

The protocol retains a portion

Only part of the supplied liquidity is borrowed

The supplier rate will generally be lower than the borrowing rate.

The difference may compensate for:

Protocol reserves

Risk funds

Operating incentives

Unused liquidity

A lender should not expect the borrowing APR to equal the supply APY.

### Utilisation Rate

The utilisation rate measures how much supplied liquidity has been borrowed.

The simplified formula is:

Utilisation = Borrowed amount ÷ Supplied amount × 100

Suppose:

Total supplied: 10 million units

Total borrowed: 7 million units

Utilisation:

7 million ÷ 10 million × 100 = 70 percent

Three million units remain available before considering reserves and other restrictions.

Utilisation is a central input in many DeFi interest-rate models.

### Interest-Rate Curves

Many protocols adjust interest rates automatically according to utilisation.

### Low Utilisation

When little capital is borrowed:

Borrowing rates may be low

Supplier yields may be low

The protocol may try to encourage borrowing

### High Utilisation

When most liquidity is borrowed:

Borrowing rates may rise

Supplier yields may rise

Higher rates encourage repayment

Higher returns may attract new deposits

The rate curve attempts to maintain sufficient liquidity for withdrawals and new borrowing.

### The Kink Model

Some lending markets use an interest-rate curve with a target utilisation point, sometimes called a kink.

Below the target:

Rates rise gradually

Above the target:

Rates rise sharply

Suppose the target utilisation is eighty percent.

The protocol may tolerate increasing borrowing up to that point.

Beyond eighty percent, borrowing becomes much more expensive.

This is intended to:

Encourage debt repayment

Attract more suppliers

Protect withdrawal liquidity

A borrower should understand how rapidly the rate can change above the target.

### Variable Borrowing Rates

A variable rate changes according to market utilisation and protocol rules.

Potential advantages include:

Efficient response to supply and demand

Lower cost during periods of abundant liquidity

Transparent formula-based adjustment

Potential risks include:

Sudden rate increases

Uncertain future costs

Negative leveraged-yield spreads

Faster debt growth

A borrowing strategy that is profitable at three percent may become unprofitable if the rate rises to fifteen percent.

### Fixed or Stable Borrowing Rates

Some protocols offer a rate intended to remain more stable.

This may provide:

Greater cost predictability

Easier planning

Reduced exposure to short-term utilisation changes

However, the rate may not be permanently fixed.

The protocol may rebalance or change it when:

Market conditions become extreme

Liquidity changes materially

Governance adjusts the model

The position violates protocol rules

Read the definition carefully.

“Stable” does not necessarily mean legally fixed for the full loan term.

### Supply APR and APY

Lending dashboards may display:

Supply APR

Supply APY

Borrow APR

Borrow APY

APR generally excludes compounding.

APY generally assumes compounding.

Rates may be calculated from:

Current utilisation

Recent block activity

Incentive-token values

Historical averages

An annualised number can change within minutes.

It should be viewed as a current estimate rather than a one-year guarantee.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',3,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-28-lesson-04','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Reserve Factor and Liquidation Bonus','cmf-module-2-28','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Reserve Factor and Liquidation Bonus, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Reserve Factor

The reserve factor determines what portion of borrower interest is retained by the protocol rather than paid to suppliers.

Suppose borrowers pay 10,000 units of interest.

If the reserve factor is ten percent:

1,000 units go to protocol reserves

9,000 units are available for suppliers, subject to other calculations

Reserves may help cover:

Bad debt

Security incidents

Protocol development

Governance-approved spending

A large reserve factor lowers lender returns but may improve protocol resilience.

### Protocol Reserves

A lending protocol may accumulate reserves in several assets.

These funds may be used for:

Absorbing bad debt

Supporting liquidity

Emergency response

Incentives

Treasury spending

Evaluate:

Reserve size

Asset quality

Liquidity

Governance control

Historical usage

Whether reserves are sufficient under stress

A reserve dominated by the protocol’s own token may lose value during the same event that creates losses.

### Lending Incentives

Protocols may reward lenders and borrowers with additional tokens.

A borrower may even receive incentives that partially or temporarily exceed the interest cost.

The displayed net rate may therefore appear:

Very low

Zero

Negative

A negative net borrowing rate means token incentives currently exceed borrowing interest.

This condition may not last.

The incentive token may:

Fall in price

Become less liquid

Be reduced by governance

Be subject to vesting

Create tax obligations

The contractual debt remains even if the incentive disappears.

### Gross Versus Net Borrowing Cost

A borrower should calculate:

Net borrowing cost = Interest + fees − incentives received

This calculation should also consider:

Incentive-token price changes

Claiming costs

Tax

Slippage when selling rewards

Opportunity cost of collateral

Liquidation risk

A borrowing strategy that appears profitable from headline rates may be negative after all costs.

### Lender Yield Sources

A lender’s return may come from:

Borrower interest

Protocol incentives

Fee distributions

Treasury subsidies

External strategy income

Each component should be separated.

Borrower interest may be more economically sustainable than temporary token issuance.

However, it still depends on:

Borrowing demand

Collateral quality

Liquidation performance

Protocol security

A high supplier yield can signal high demand, but it can also signal market stress and liquidity shortage.

### Withdrawal Liquidity

A lender may be able to withdraw only if sufficient unborrowed liquidity remains in the pool.

Suppose:

Ten million units are supplied

Nine-and-a-half million are borrowed

Only five hundred thousand remain

A lender attempting to withdraw one million may be unable to do so immediately.

The protocol may require:

Other suppliers to deposit

Borrowers to repay

Liquidations to occur

Interest rates to attract liquidity

A position can be economically solvent but temporarily illiquid.

### Withdrawal Queues

Some lending systems use withdrawal queues when immediate liquidity is unavailable.

A user may submit a withdrawal request and wait until:

Borrowers repay

New lenders deposit

Assets mature

Collateral is liquidated

The protocol processes the queue

The queue may function normally during calm conditions and grow during stress.

Before lending, determine whether withdrawals are:

Immediate

Best effort

Queue-based

Subject to lock-ups

Controlled by a company or governance process

### Liquidity Mismatch

Liquidity mismatch occurs when lenders expect short-term access while borrowers use funds for longer or less liquid activities.

This is common in conventional banking and can also occur in cryptocurrency lending.

For example:

Depositors expect instant withdrawals

The platform makes long-term or illiquid loans

Many depositors withdraw simultaneously

The platform cannot return assets immediately

Decentralised pooled lending reduces some forms of opacity, but highly utilised pools can still experience withdrawal pressure.

Centralised lenders may have even greater mismatch when their loan book is not publicly visible.

### Liquidation

Liquidation protects the protocol when collateral value becomes insufficient.

A liquidator repays part of the borrower’s debt.

In return, the liquidator receives collateral, usually at a discount.

This process:

Reduces outstanding debt

Restores the position’s safety

Rewards the liquidator

Protects lenders from bad debt

For the borrower, liquidation creates:

Collateral loss

A penalty

Reduced future exposure

Potential tax consequences

The mechanism is automatic and does not wait for the borrower’s permission.

### Liquidation Bonus

The liquidation bonus is the discount or incentive paid to the liquidator.

Suppose:

A liquidator repays 1,000 units of debt

Liquidation bonus: 5 percent

The liquidator may receive collateral worth approximately:

1,000 × 1.05 = 1,050 units

The extra fifty units compensates for:

Transaction fees

Execution risk

Market volatility

Competition

The need to sell collateral

The bonus is effectively paid from the borrower’s collateral.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',4,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-28-lesson-05','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Close Factor and Stablecoin Borrowing','cmf-module-2-28','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Close Factor and Stablecoin Borrowing, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Close Factor

A close factor may limit how much debt can be liquidated in one transaction.

For example, a protocol may allow a liquidator to repay no more than fifty percent of the outstanding debt at once.

This can prevent unnecessary full liquidation after a small threshold breach.

However, severe conditions may permit larger or complete liquidation.

The exact rules differ between protocols and can change through governance.

### Partial and Full Liquidation



### Partial Liquidation

Only part of the debt is repaid and part of the collateral is removed.

The position may remain open with an improved health factor.

### Full Liquidation

The entire position is closed or most collateral is sold.

This may occur when:

The position is deeply undercollateralised

Protocol rules allow complete closure

Market prices move rapidly

Collateral liquidity deteriorates

Borrowers should not assume liquidation will be a small or gradual event.

### Liquidation Price

A borrower may calculate the approximate collateral price at which liquidation begins.

Suppose:

One collateral token is deposited

Its current value is 2,000 units

Debt is 1,000 units

Liquidation threshold is 75 percent

Liquidation begins when:

Collateral value × 75 percent = Debt

Required collateral value:

1,000 ÷ 0.75 = approximately 1,333.33 units

If the token price falls from 2,000 to approximately 1,333, the position reaches the threshold before accounting for interest growth and fees.

The actual liquidation level changes as debt accrues.

### Maintaining a Safety Buffer

A borrower can reduce liquidation risk by:

Borrowing less

Depositing more collateral

Repaying part of the debt

Using less volatile collateral

Monitoring interest

Maintaining liquid funds for emergency repayment

A larger buffer provides more time to respond.

It does not eliminate:

Flash crashes

Oracle errors

Network congestion

Stablecoin depegging

Protocol failure

A position should be safe enough to survive realistic stress, not only ordinary daily volatility.

### Liquidation Cascades

A liquidation cascade occurs when falling prices trigger forced collateral sales that push prices lower and cause additional liquidations.

A simplified sequence is:

Collateral price falls

Health factors decline

Positions become liquidatable

Liquidators sell collateral

Selling pressure lowers the price

More positions become eligible

The cycle continues

Cascades may be amplified by:

Leverage

Thin liquidity

Correlated collateral

Stablecoin stress

Exchange liquidations

Network congestion

A protocol’s risk model should consider how much collateral can realistically be sold during severe market stress.

### Bad Debt

Bad debt occurs when the value recovered from collateral is insufficient to repay the borrower’s debt fully.

Possible causes include:

Rapid price gaps

Illiquid collateral

Delayed oracle updates

Network congestion

Failed liquidations

Smart contract errors

Collateral depegging

Bad debt may be absorbed by:

Protocol reserves

Insurance funds

Governance treasury

Suppliers

A protocol-token auction

Socialised losses

Users should understand who ultimately bears the loss.

### Socialised Losses

Socialised losses occur when losses from one part of the system are distributed across other users.

For example, suppliers may receive less than expected because the pool contains unrecoverable debt.

The protocol may reduce:

Redemption value

Interest payments

Available withdrawals

Token backing

A lending platform may advertise overcollateralisation while still exposing suppliers to bad debt under extreme conditions.

### Oracle Dependence

Lending protocols require reliable asset prices to calculate:

Collateral value

Borrowing capacity

Health factors

Liquidation thresholds

Liquidation payments

A price oracle supplies this information.

If the oracle reports an incorrect value, the protocol may:

Liquidate healthy borrowers

Allow excessive borrowing

Misprice collateral

Accumulate bad debt

Oracle design is therefore a critical part of lending security.

### Oracle Manipulation

An attacker may attempt to manipulate a low-liquidity market used by the oracle.

A simplified attack could involve:

Borrowing large temporary capital

Trading aggressively in a shallow market

Distorting the reported collateral price

Borrowing excessive assets against the inflated collateral

Allowing the collateral price to return to normal

Leaving the protocol with bad debt

Strong oracle systems may use:

Multiple exchanges

Time-weighted averages

Independent data providers

Price-deviation limits

Circuit breakers

Minimum liquidity requirements

### Stale Oracle Data

An oracle may fail to update quickly during market volatility.

If the reported price is too old:

Borrowers may withdraw too much

Liquidations may be delayed

Healthy positions may be misclassified

Protocol losses may increase

The protocol should define:

Update frequency

Maximum acceptable delay

Fallback sources

Emergency behaviour

A highly secure smart contract can still fail economically when it receives poor data.

### Stablecoin Borrowing

Borrowing stablecoins is common because they provide a relatively stable unit of account.

A borrower may deposit volatile collateral and borrow a stablecoin.

This creates a leveraged exposure to the collateral asset.

Suppose:

The borrower deposits a cryptocurrency

Borrows stablecoins

Uses the stablecoins for expenses

Retains the collateral

If the collateral rises, the borrower benefits from continued exposure.

If it falls, liquidation risk increases.

The debt remains denominated in the stablecoin.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',5,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-28-lesson-06','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Stablecoin Depeg Risk for Borrowers and Token Listing Risk','cmf-module-2-28','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Stablecoin Depeg Risk for Borrowers and Token Listing Risk, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Stablecoin Depeg Risk for Borrowers

A stablecoin debt may become more or less expensive if the stablecoin loses its peg.

Suppose a borrower owes 10,000 stablecoin units.

If each unit rises above its intended value, repaying the debt becomes more expensive in external currency terms.

If the stablecoin falls below its peg, repayment may become cheaper—but the protocol or market may experience broader instability.

The borrower is exposed to both:

Collateral price

Debt-asset stability

### Stablecoin Lending Risk

A lender supplying stablecoins faces risks involving:

Stablecoin issuer

Reserve quality

Redemption

Regulation

Smart contract

Borrower collateral

Protocol liquidity

A five-percent stablecoin yield is not equivalent to risk-free cash interest.

The lender may lose through:

Depegging

Protocol exploit

Bad debt

Withdrawal restrictions

Issuer freezing

Bridge failure

### Borrowing Volatile Assets

A user may borrow a volatile cryptocurrency instead of a stablecoin.

This creates a short-like exposure.

Suppose the borrower:

Borrows Asset A

Sells it for a stablecoin

Plans to repurchase it later at a lower price

Repays the loan

If Asset A falls, the strategy may profit.

If Asset A rises, the debt becomes more expensive.

Potential losses can be very large because an asset’s price has no fixed maximum.

Borrowing a volatile asset involves substantial market risk in addition to interest and liquidation risk.

### Collateral Correlation

Collateral risk depends partly on its relationship with the borrowed asset.

Suppose a user deposits one volatile token and borrows another highly correlated token.

Both may decline together, but the exact effect depends on their relative movement.

A protocol may offer higher collateral efficiency for closely related assets because their prices historically move together.

This introduces correlation-break risk.

Assets that normally track one another can diverge during stress.

### Efficiency Modes

Some protocols offer specialised borrowing modes for highly correlated assets.

These modes may allow:

Higher LTV

Lower liquidation buffers

Greater capital efficiency

Examples may include borrowing one stablecoin against another or borrowing an underlying asset against its liquid-staking token.

The higher efficiency depends on the assumption that the assets remain closely linked.

If one depegs or redemption fails, liquidation can occur rapidly.

Capital efficiency increases when safety margins decrease.

### Isolated Collateral

In an isolated market, a specific collateral asset can support borrowing only under restricted conditions.

The protocol may limit:

Which asset may be borrowed

Maximum total debt

LTV

Exposure to the rest of the system

Isolation helps contain the damage if a riskier collateral asset fails.

It reduces contagion between markets.

Users should determine whether their position is isolated and what restrictions apply.

### Cross-Collateral Borrowing

Cross-collateral systems combine several collateral assets into one borrowing account.

Potential advantages include:

Greater capital efficiency

Simplified portfolio borrowing

Offsetting collateral values

Potential risks include:

One weak asset endangering the entire account

Liquidation across multiple holdings

Complex risk calculation

Correlation during market stress

A user may lose high-quality collateral because a smaller speculative collateral position deteriorates.

### Cross-Margin Risk

Cross-margin structures use the value of several positions to support total debt.

Losses in one position can consume collateral associated with another.

This may delay liquidation initially but increase the eventual loss.

The user should understand whether:

Each position is independent

All collateral supports all debt

Liquidators can seize any collateral

Risk can spread across the account

Efficiency and contagion often increase together.

### Supply Caps and Borrow Caps

Protocols may limit how much of an asset can be supplied or borrowed.

### Supply Cap

Limits total collateral or deposits accepted.

### Borrow Cap

Limits total borrowing of an asset.

Caps can reduce exposure to:

Illiquid tokens

Oracle manipulation

Concentrated collateral

Sudden market expansion

If caps are reached, users may be unable to deposit or borrow more.

Governance may adjust the limits over time.

### Debt Ceilings

A debt ceiling limits how much debt can be created against a particular collateral type.

This is particularly useful for higher-risk or isolated assets.

A low ceiling contains potential losses if the collateral fails.

A rapidly increasing ceiling may signal that governance is accepting greater system exposure.

Risk parameters should be reviewed as part of protocol governance analysis.

### Token Listing Risk

A lending protocol must decide which assets are accepted as collateral or borrowable markets.

Adding a new token can create:

New fee and borrowing demand

Greater protocol usage

Oracle risk

Liquidity risk

Governance conflict

Bad-debt risk

A token may be unsuitable as collateral when it has:

Concentrated ownership

Low liquidity

Changeable transfer rules

High volatility

Weak oracles

Large unlocks

Bridge dependence

Listing is a risk decision, not merely a growth feature.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',6,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-28-lesson-07','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Governance Risk and Leveraged Short Strategy','cmf-module-2-28','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Governance Risk and Leveraged Short Strategy, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Governance Risk

Governance may control:

Collateral factors

Liquidation thresholds

Interest-rate models

Reserve factors

Asset listings

Supply and borrow caps

Oracle providers

Contract upgrades

Treasury use

A poorly designed or malicious proposal can change the safety of existing positions.

Users should monitor governance when they hold meaningful lending or borrowing exposure.

### Administrator Powers

A protocol may have administrator keys that can:

Pause markets

Freeze borrowing

Change risk parameters

Upgrade contracts

Replace oracles

Recover assets

Restrict withdrawals

Emergency powers can protect users during an exploit.

They also create centralisation and key-compromise risk.

Review:

Who controls the keys

Whether a multisignature is used

Whether changes have a timelock

Whether emergency actions are publicly documented

### Smart Contract Risk

Lending contracts may contain vulnerabilities involving:

Interest calculations

Collateral accounting

Token transfers

Liquidation logic

Access controls

Upgradeability

Price oracles

Re-entrancy

Flash loans

An exploit may:

Drain supplied assets

Create artificial collateral

Prevent withdrawals

Produce bad debt

Manipulate interest

Audits reduce risk but cannot guarantee safety.

### Economic Design Risk

The code may function exactly as intended while the economic model fails.

Examples include:

Collateral limits set too high

Liquidation bonuses set too low

Poorly designed interest curves

Weak withdrawal incentives

Inadequate reserves

Risky collateral accepted

Oracle markets too shallow

Protocol evaluation must consider both software and financial design.

### Flash Loans

A flash loan is borrowed and repaid within one blockchain transaction.

No ordinary collateral is required because the transaction reverses if repayment does not occur.

Flash loans may support:

Arbitrage

Debt refinancing

Collateral swaps

Liquidations

Interest-rate optimisation

They may also fund attacks involving:

Oracle manipulation

Governance exploits

Low-liquidity collateral

Economic-design weaknesses

The flash loan is usually the source of temporary capital, not the underlying vulnerability.

### Credit Delegation

Credit delegation occurs when one user allows another user to borrow against their supplied capital or credit line.

The delegator accepts some form of borrower risk.

The arrangement may use:

Legal agreements

Whitelists

Smart contracts

Institutional underwriting

On-chain reputation

Unlike ordinary overcollateralised lending, credit delegation may expose the lender more directly to default.

Users should understand:

Who the borrower is

Which recourse exists

Whether the loan is secured

How losses are allocated

### Undercollateralised Lending

Undercollateralised lending allows borrowing with collateral worth less than the loan.

This resembles conventional credit more closely.

It requires some substitute for full on-chain collateral, such as:

Identity

Credit assessment

Legal agreements

Future income

Institutional reputation

Insurance

Community guarantees

Potential use cases include:

Business credit

Market-maker financing

Trade finance

Real-world lending

The system introduces greater default, legal and enforcement risk.

Permissionless overcollateralised lending and undercollateralised credit should not be treated as the same product.

### Real-World Asset Lending

Blockchain protocols may finance loans connected to real-world assets or borrowers.

Possible collateral or repayment sources include:

Property

Invoices

Loans

Bonds

Business revenue

Equipment

Commodities

These systems may use blockchain records and tokens while relying heavily on off-chain institutions.

Risks include:

Legal enforceability

Asset custody

Valuation

Fraud

Servicing

Jurisdiction

Borrower default

Bankruptcy procedures

Tokenisation does not remove conventional credit risk.

### Rehypothecation

Rehypothecation occurs when deposited or pledged assets are reused in additional financial activities.

A centralised lender may lend customer assets to another institution.

A DeFi user may deposit a lending receipt token into another protocol.

This can create multiple layers of claims.

Potential benefits include:

Greater capital efficiency

Additional yield

More available credit

Potential risks include:

Contagion

Unclear asset ownership

Complex liquidation

Several protocols depending on the same collateral

The same economic value may support multiple positions.

### Recursive Borrowing

Recursive borrowing, also called looping, repeatedly deposits and borrows assets to increase exposure.

A simplified strategy may be:

Deposit collateral

Borrow an asset

Use the borrowed asset to buy more collateral

Deposit the additional collateral

Borrow again

Repeat

This increases effective leverage.

It may also increase:

Interest cost

Liquidation sensitivity

Transaction fees

Smart contract exposure

Unwinding complexity

### Leveraged Long Strategy

Suppose a user expects Asset A to rise.

They may:

Deposit Asset A

Borrow stablecoins

Buy more Asset A

Deposit it as additional collateral

The user now has greater exposure to Asset A than their original capital.

If the asset rises, gains are amplified.

If it falls, losses and liquidation risk are amplified.

This is a leveraged long position, even though it may appear as several lending transactions.

### Leveraged Short Strategy

A user expecting Asset A to fall may:

Deposit stablecoin collateral

Borrow Asset A

Sell Asset A for stablecoins

Repurchase it later at a lower price

Repay the debt

If Asset A rises, the debt becomes more expensive and may threaten the collateral.

Short exposure can create very large losses.

Borrowing should be analysed according to its economic direction, not only its interface.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',7,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-28-lesson-08','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Yield Looping and Lender Risk Analysis','cmf-module-2-28','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Yield Looping and Lender Risk Analysis, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Yield Looping

A user may borrow to increase yield exposure.

For example:

Deposit a liquid-staking token

Borrow the underlying asset

Stake or convert it into more LST

Deposit again

The strategy may earn the difference between:

Staking yield

Borrowing cost

It also adds:

Leverage

LST depeg risk

Liquidation risk

Variable rates

Smart contract dependencies

A small negative change in the yield spread can make the strategy unprofitable.

### Net Yield Spread

A simplified leveraged-yield calculation is:

Net spread = Yield earned − Borrowing cost − fees

Suppose:

Staking yield: 7 percent

Borrowing rate: 4 percent

Other annualised costs: 1 percent

Approximate net spread:

7 − 4 − 1 = 2 percent

The two-percent spread may not justify:

Liquidation risk

Smart contract risk

Rate variability

Depegging

Operational complexity

Returns should be compared with the full risk, not only the positive spread.

### Rate Inversion

Rate inversion occurs when borrowing costs rise above the yield earned.

Suppose a strategy earns six percent while the borrowing rate rises to nine percent.

The position now loses approximately three percent annually before other costs.

The borrower may need to:

Repay debt

Reduce leverage

Accept negative carry

Wait for rates to change

High utilisation can cause rate inversion rapidly.

### Liquidation During Network Congestion

A borrower may plan to add collateral or repay debt during a decline.

During network congestion:

Transactions may remain pending

Fees may rise sharply

The user’s transaction may fail

Liquidators may use faster execution

Front-end interfaces may become overloaded

A position that requires immediate manual action is not truly safe.

Maintain enough buffer to account for operational delays.

### Liquidator Competition

Liquidations can be profitable.

Automated liquidators compete to identify and close eligible positions.

They may use:

Bots

Private transaction routing

High network fees

Specialised infrastructure

Flash loans

Borrowers should not assume they will receive a warning period.

Once a position becomes eligible, automated systems may liquidate it almost immediately.

### MEV and Liquidations

Maximum Extractable Value may affect liquidation ordering.

Block producers or specialised traders may compete to place profitable liquidation transactions first.

This can improve protocol solvency by encouraging rapid liquidation.

It can also:

Increase network fees

Create transaction-ordering advantages

Exclude ordinary participants

Concentrate liquidation profits

The system relies on economic incentives to protect lenders.

### Deleveraging

Deleveraging reduces borrowing exposure.

A borrower may:

Repay part of the debt

Add collateral

Sell part of the collateral to repay

Close recursive loops

Move to less volatile collateral

Deleveraging is easier before market stress becomes severe.

Waiting until the health factor approaches liquidation may leave few practical options.

### Collateral Swaps

Some protocols allow borrowers to replace one collateral asset with another without closing the entire loan.

Potential benefits include:

Reducing volatility

Changing market exposure

Avoiding several manual transactions

Improving the health factor

Risks include:

Slippage

Smart contract complexity

Temporary exposure during the swap

Tax consequences

Oracle movement

The borrower should confirm that the final collateral remains appropriate and liquid.

### Debt Refinancing

A borrower may move debt between:

Assets

Protocols

Fixed and variable rates

Different blockchains

Refinancing may reduce interest or improve collateral efficiency.

It introduces:

Bridge risk

Transaction fees

Smart contract risk

Timing risk

Temporary double exposure

New governance rules

A lower displayed rate may not justify moving to a weaker protocol.

### Self-Repaying or Yield-Assisted Loans

Some systems use the yield generated by collateral to reduce debt over time.

A simplified structure may involve:

The user deposits a yield-generating asset

The protocol lends or stakes it

Generated yield repays the debt

The principal collateral remains locked

The loan is not literally guaranteed to repay itself.

Repayment depends on:

Yield continuing

Collateral remaining safe

Protocol solvency

Fees

No exploit

Sufficient time

If yield declines or losses occur, repayment may take longer or fail.

### Borrower Risk Analysis

A borrower should evaluate:

Collateral volatility

Borrowed asset stability

Interest-rate variability

Liquidation threshold

Health factor

Unbonding or withdrawal restrictions

Network congestion

Oracle quality

Protocol security

Repayment liquidity

The borrower should also ask:

What will happen if the collateral falls fifty percent while the borrowing rate doubles?

A strategy that cannot survive a severe but plausible scenario may be oversized.

### Lender Risk Analysis

A lender should evaluate:

Borrower demand

Collateral quality

Liquidation design

Oracle reliability

Available withdrawal liquidity

Reserve adequacy

Bad-debt history

Smart contract security

Incentive sustainability

Stablecoin or token risk

The lender’s return is compensation for providing capital to a credit system.

It should not be judged by yield alone.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',8,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
