INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-29-lesson-12','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Layer 1 and Layer 2 Checklist and Module Summary','cmf-module-2-29','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Layer 1 and Layer 2 Checklist and Module Summary, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Layer 1 and Layer 2 Checklist

Before transferring assets to a network, ask:

Is this a Layer 1, Layer 2, sidechain or another architecture?

Which functions does the network perform independently?

Which Layer 1, if any, provides settlement?

Does the base chain verify transaction correctness?

Is the system optimistic or validity-proof based?

Are fraud or validity proofs fully operational?

Where is transaction data stored?

Can users reconstruct the state independently?

Who operates the sequencer?

Can users bypass the sequencer?

What happens if the sequencer goes offline?

Who generates proofs?

Who can upgrade contracts?

Is a timelock used?

Which emergency powers exist?

Can administrators freeze or redirect assets?

Which bridge will be used?

Is it the canonical bridge or a third-party bridge?

What withdrawal period applies?

Is a fast withdrawal dependent on a liquidity provider?

Is the destination asset native, wrapped or bridged?

Who guarantees its backing?

Is sufficient liquidity available?

Which token is required for network fees?

Do I have enough gas for emergency transactions?

Is the receiving exchange or wallet compatible with the network?

What is the total cost of entering and exiting?

How mature is the network?

Has it experienced outages or security incidents?

Can I test the route with a small amount?

Is the network appropriate for the value and purpose of the transaction?

### Common Layer 1 and Layer 2 Mistakes



### Choosing Only by Transaction Fee

Security, liquidity and exit risk are ignored.

### Assuming Every Connected Chain Is a Layer 2

A sidechain may rely on its own smaller validator set.

### Treating Fast Confirmation as Final Settlement

The transaction may not yet be final on the settlement layer.

### Using the Wrong Asset Representation

The user accepts an unsupported or weakly backed bridged token.

### Using an Unverified Bridge

A counterfeit or insecure bridge contract receives the assets.

### Ignoring Withdrawal Delays

The user expects immediate return to Layer 1.

### Holding No Gas Token

Assets cannot be moved during an emergency.

### Assuming the Same Application Has Identical Risk on Every Network

Contracts, liquidity and oracles can differ.

### Treating a Familiar Token Symbol as Proof of Authenticity

Several versions may exist on the same network.

### Ignoring Administrator Powers

A small group may be able to upgrade or pause the system.

### Believing ZK Automatically Means Private

Validity proofs and privacy are separate concepts.

### Confusing High Transaction Count With High-Quality Adoption

Bots and incentives may create temporary activity.

### Common Misunderstandings

#### “Layer 2 Transactions Occur Completely Off-Chain”

They are processed outside ordinary Layer 1 execution but may publish data and commitments to the Layer 1.

#### “Every Layer 2 Has the Same Security as Its Layer 1”

Sequencers, bridges, administrators and data systems introduce additional assumptions.

#### “A Sidechain Is Simply Another Type of Rollup”

A sidechain generally relies on its own consensus rather than Layer 1 verification.

#### “Optimistic Rollups Are Insecure Because They Assume Validity”

They use challenge and fraud-proof mechanisms, though these must operate effectively.

#### “ZK Rollups Have No Risks”

Proof systems, circuits, provers, bridges and administrators can fail.

#### “Zero Knowledge Means Nobody Can See Transactions”

A validity proof can be zero knowledge while transaction data remains public.

#### “Low Fees Mean the Network Is More Efficient in Every Way”

Low fees may reflect different security, demand or decentralisation trade-offs.

#### “A Transaction Is Final When the Wallet Says Confirmed”

Initial Layer 2 confirmation may precede final Layer 1 settlement.

#### “Canonical Bridged Assets and Third-Party Wrapped Assets Are Identical”

They may depend on different contracts, custodians and redemption paths.

#### “High TVL Proves a Layer 2 Is Safe”

TVL measures deposited value, not proof quality or governance decentralisation.

#### “More Layers Always Improve Scalability Without Cost”

Every additional layer creates new dependencies and coordination risks.

#### “Layer 2 Growth Automatically Makes Its Token Valuable”

The token may capture little or none of the network’s economic activity.

### Module Summary

A Layer 1 is a base blockchain that operates its own consensus and authoritative transaction history.

It may provide:

Execution

Consensus

Settlement

Data availability

Security

A Layer 2 processes activity more efficiently while relying on a Layer 1 for important settlement or verification functions.

Rollups batch many transactions and submit compressed information to a Layer 1.

Optimistic rollups generally assume batches are valid unless challenged through fraud proofs.

Zero-knowledge rollups use cryptographic validity proofs to demonstrate correct execution.

Layer 2 networks may depend on:

Sequencers

Provers

Fraud monitors

Data-availability systems

Bridges

Administrator keys

Governance

A sidechain differs from a Layer 2 because it generally relies on its own consensus and validator set rather than inheriting the base chain’s transaction-validity security.

Scaling can reduce fees and increase capacity.

It can also create:

Liquidity fragmentation

Bridge risk

Additional governance layers

Data-availability risk

Complex withdrawal procedures

New centralisation points

A network should not be selected according to transaction fees alone.

Users should evaluate:

Security

Settlement

Data availability

Liquidity

Asset representation

Bridge design

Administrator powers

Withdrawal path

Total transaction cost

Layer 1 and Layer 2 systems are not competitors in every case.

They can form a layered architecture in which the Layer 1 provides high-value settlement and Layer 2 networks provide more affordable execution.

The strength of that architecture depends on whether every layer remains verifiable, accessible and secure.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',12,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
