INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-30-lesson-06','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Leverage Policy and Information Sources','cmf-module-2-30','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Leverage Policy and Information Sources, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Leverage Policy

A personal framework should state whether leverage is permitted.

Possible policy choices include:

No leverage

Leverage allowed only in a separate trading account

Maximum effective leverage

Maximum liquidation risk

Prohibition on borrowing against core holdings

Prohibition on recursive lending

Leverage increases:

Loss speed

Liquidation risk

Emotional pressure

Dependency on exchanges and protocols

No position should use leverage merely because the platform makes it available.

### DeFi Participation Policy

A DeFi policy may define:

Approved protocols

Maximum exposure per protocol

Minimum operating history

Audit requirements

Prohibited leverage

Permitted stablecoins

Wallet separation

Approval-revocation practices

Exit procedures

Every DeFi position should identify:

Yield source

Smart contracts

Collateral

Oracle

Bridge

Governance

Withdrawal conditions

The displayed yield should never replace this analysis.

### Staking Policy

A staking policy may include:

Permitted assets

Validator-selection rules

Maximum custodial exposure

Unbonding limits

Liquid-staking-token limits

Restaking restrictions

Slashing review

Reward-recording procedures

The framework should aggregate:

Native tokens

Staked tokens

Liquid-staking tokens

Restaked positions

as related underlying exposure.

### Lending and Borrowing Policy

A lending policy may define:

Approved protocols

Permitted collateral

Maximum supplier exposure

Minimum withdrawal liquidity

Stablecoin standards

Required reserve analysis

A borrowing policy may define:

Maximum LTV

Minimum health factor

Emergency repayment reserve

Prohibition on borrowing for speculation

Maximum variable interest rate

No borrowing near liquidation thresholds

Borrowing should have a clear purpose and repayment plan.

### Stablecoin Policy

Stablecoins may be used for:

Trading liquidity

DeFi

Portfolio reserves

Payments

The framework should evaluate:

Issuer

Reserve assets

Redemption

Regulation

Blockchain

Bridge

Liquidity

Freezing powers

Possible rules include:

Maximum exposure to one stablecoin

Preference for native rather than bridged versions

No long-term reserve in unaudited or weakly backed tokens

Depeg-response procedures

Stablecoins should not be treated as identical to insured bank deposits.

### Custody Framework

Custody should match:

Position size

Holding period

Transaction frequency

Technical ability

Recovery needs

A custody structure may separate:

### Long-Term Wallet

For assets that rarely interact with applications.

### Active Wallet

For regular transactions.

### DeFi Wallet

For approved smart contract activity.

### Experimental Wallet

For small, high-risk interactions.

### Exchange Balance

Only for capital needed for trading or short-term operations.

The objective is to reduce single points of failure.

### Exchange Exposure Limits

Assets held on an exchange are exposed to:

Insolvency

Hacking

Withdrawal suspension

Account restriction

Regulatory action

Operational failure

A framework may limit:

Maximum value per exchange

Duration of exchange custody

Assets permitted to remain

Withdrawal-test frequency

Authentication requirements

Exchange convenience should not create unlimited counterparty exposure.

### Wallet Security Standards

Security requirements may include:

Hardware wallet for significant holdings

Offline recovery backup

Strong device security

Separate passwords

Multifactor authentication

Address verification

Small test transactions

No storage of seed phrases in cloud notes

Regular approval review

A documented inheritance or recovery plan

Security should be designed before the portfolio becomes large.

### Recovery Planning

A recovery plan should address:

Lost device

Damaged hardware wallet

Forgotten password

Death or incapacity

Compromised seed phrase

Fire or theft

Wallet software failure

The plan must balance:

Security

Accessibility

Privacy

Simplicity

A recovery method that is so complex that the owner cannot use it is not effective.

Do not store all recovery components in one vulnerable location.

### Transaction Procedures

A personal transaction checklist may require:

Verify the recipient address

Verify the blockchain network

Confirm the asset contract

Check any memo or tag

Send a small test amount

Confirm receipt

Send the remaining amount

Record the transaction

For smart contract interactions:

Verify the application

Verify the contract

Review approvals

Check minimum received

Examine fees and slippage

Confirm the wallet request

Revoke unnecessary permissions later

A repeatable procedure reduces operational mistakes.

### Tax and Record-Keeping Framework

The framework should record:

Purchases

Sales

Swaps

Transfers

Fees

Staking rewards

Lending interest

Airdrops

Liquidity-provider transactions

Liquidations

Wallet ownership

Cost basis

Records should include:

Date

Quantity

Asset

Market value

Transaction identifier

Platform

Purpose

Tax treatment differs by jurisdiction.

Record-keeping should begin with the first transaction rather than after the portfolio becomes complex.

### Regulatory Review

The investor should establish a schedule for reviewing:

Tax rules

Exchange restrictions

Stablecoin regulations

Staking treatment

DeFi access

Reporting requirements

Securities classification

Foreign exchange controls

Regulatory changes can alter:

Asset liquidity

Platform availability

Tax cost

Custody options

Project viability

The framework should allow adaptation without panic.

### Information Sources

A strong research process uses several source types.

Possible sources include:

Official documentation

Source-code repositories

Blockchain explorers

Governance forums

Audit reports

Development updates

Independent research

Regulatory publications

Financial statements

On-chain data

Avoid relying only on:

Promotional videos

Influencer posts

Anonymous screenshots

Community rumours

Price predictions

Referral-driven content

Primary evidence should receive greater weight than commentary.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',6,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-30-lesson-07','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Source Verification and Sunk-Cost Fallacy','cmf-module-2-30','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Source Verification and Sunk-Cost Fallacy, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Source Verification

Before accepting information, ask:

Who produced it?

What incentives do they have?

Is the data independently verifiable?

Is it current?

Does another credible source confirm it?

Is the claim based on evidence or opinion?

A project’s own documentation is useful for understanding its stated design.

It should not be treated as independent proof that the design will succeed.

### Research Frequency

Different information requires different review frequency.

### Frequent Monitoring

May apply to:

Leveraged positions

DeFi collateral

Security incidents

Liquidation levels

Major governance proposals

### Periodic Monitoring

May apply to:

Adoption

Development

Token unlocks

Portfolio allocations

Regulatory changes

### Event-Driven Monitoring

May apply when:

A major upgrade occurs

The project is exploited

Leadership changes

A stablecoin depegs

A major unlock approaches

Monitoring should match the position’s risk and time horizon.

### Investment Journal

An investment journal records the reasoning behind decisions.

Entries may include:

Date

Asset

Thesis

Evidence

Valuation

Entry reason

Position size

Risks

Invalidation

Emotional state

Expected time horizon

Planned review date

Later updates can record:

New evidence

Changes to the thesis

Position adjustments

Outcome

Lessons learned

The purpose is to evaluate decision quality—not merely whether the price rose.

### Decision Quality Versus Outcome

A good decision can produce a loss.

A poor decision can produce a profit.

For example:

A disciplined, researched position may fail because of an unexpected event

An impulsive meme-token purchase may rise through luck

Judging decisions only by outcomes encourages poor habits.

Evaluate whether the decision:

Followed the framework

Used reliable evidence

Applied appropriate sizing

Considered alternatives

Managed risk

The goal is a process capable of producing acceptable results across many decisions.

### Behavioural Biases

Investors are influenced by predictable psychological tendencies.

Common biases include:

Fear of missing out

Loss aversion

Anchoring

Confirmation bias

Recency bias

Overconfidence

Herd behaviour

Sunk-cost fallacy

Outcome bias

Narrative bias

A written framework creates distance between emotional reactions and financial actions.

### Fear of Missing Out

Fear of missing out, or FOMO, occurs when rising prices create pressure to buy immediately.

Possible signs include:

Ignoring valuation

Increasing position size suddenly

Buying without research

Abandoning category limits

Believing the opportunity will never return

A framework may require:

A waiting period

Completion of the research checklist

Position-size calculation

No purchase beyond the maximum allocation

Urgency is often a marketing technique rather than an investment advantage.

### Loss Aversion

Loss aversion describes the tendency to feel losses more strongly than equivalent gains.

It may cause investors to:

Hold failing assets too long

Sell winners too early

Avoid necessary rebalancing

Refuse to acknowledge thesis failure

A predefined invalidation rule can reduce this bias.

The purpose is not to eliminate discomfort.

It is to prevent discomfort from overriding evidence.

### Confirmation Bias

Confirmation bias causes people to search for information supporting their existing belief while dismissing contrary evidence.

To counter it:

Write the main risks

Search deliberately for criticism

Identify what would disprove the thesis

Review opposing analysis

Separate community enthusiasm from evidence

An investment thesis that cannot be questioned is closer to an identity or belief system than an analysis.

### Anchoring

Anchoring occurs when one number influences judgement excessively.

Common anchors include:

Purchase price

Previous all-time high

Influencer target

Initial market capitalisation

A round-number forecast

The previous price does not determine future value.

Every review should use current evidence and realistic future scenarios.

### Recency Bias

Recency bias gives excessive importance to recent events.

During a bull market, investors may believe prices will continue rising.

During a crash, they may believe recovery is impossible.

A framework should use:

Several market cycles

Long-term data

Scenario analysis

Predefined allocation limits

Recent performance is one data point, not a permanent law.

### Overconfidence

Overconfidence may develop after a series of profitable decisions.

It can lead to:

Larger positions

Increased leverage

Reduced research

Ignored risk limits

Excessive trading

Profits do not prove that the method cannot fail.

Position limits should not increase automatically after short-term success.

### Herd Behaviour

Herd behaviour occurs when participants follow the crowd because many others appear convinced.

The crowd can provide useful information.

It can also produce:

Bubbles

Panic

Mispricing

Crowded trades

Liquidity traps

The relevant question is not how many people believe the story.

It is whether the evidence and valuation support it.

### Sunk-Cost Fallacy

The sunk-cost fallacy causes investors to continue committing resources because they have already invested time or money.

Examples include:

Buying more to rescue a failing position

Refusing to exit because research took months

Supporting a project because of community involvement

Holding because the loss is already large

Past costs cannot be recovered through loyalty.

Future decisions should be based on future expected value.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',7,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-30-lesson-08','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Narrative Bias and Material Events','cmf-module-2-30','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Narrative Bias and Material Events, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Narrative Bias

Cryptocurrency markets frequently organise around compelling stories.

Examples may involve:

New financial systems

Artificial intelligence

Gaming

Tokenisation

Digital ownership

Privacy

Institutional adoption

A narrative may attract capital before genuine value is demonstrated.

The framework should require measurable evidence that the project can benefit from the narrative.

A good story does not guarantee a good token.

### Social-Media Policy

A personal framework may include rules for social-media information.

For example:

No purchases based solely on one post

Disclose whether the promoter owns the token

Verify claims through primary sources

Avoid anonymous direct-message opportunities

Never reveal seed phrases to support accounts

Do not treat follower count as expertise

Record the actual research independently

Social media can identify ideas.

It should not complete the due-diligence process.

### Cooling-Off Period

A cooling-off period is a deliberate delay between discovering an opportunity and investing.

It may be:

Several hours

One day

Several days

The length can depend on:

Position size

Asset risk

Market conditions

A delay allows:

Emotional intensity to decline

Claims to be verified

Risks to be reviewed

Position size to be calculated

Truly durable opportunities usually survive a reasonable period of analysis.

### Scenario Analysis

Scenario analysis considers several possible futures rather than one forecast.

Possible scenarios include:

### Bear Case

Adoption weakens

Token supply increases

Regulation becomes restrictive

Price declines substantially

### Base Case

Project develops gradually

Adoption grows moderately

Valuation remains reasonable

### Bull Case

Strong network effects develop

Revenue and usage increase

The project gains meaningful market share

Assigning probabilities can help compare opportunities.

The estimates remain uncertain and should be conservative.

### Expected Value

A simplified expected value can be calculated as:

Expected value = Sum of each outcome multiplied by its probability

Suppose:

Bear case: 40-percent probability, 70-percent loss

Base case: 40-percent probability, 50-percent gain

Bull case: 20-percent probability, 300-percent gain

Expected return:

0.40 × −70 + 0.40 × 50 + 0.20 × 300

−28 + 20 + 60 = 52 percent

This does not mean the investment will return fifty-two percent.

It reveals how assumptions combine.

Overly optimistic probabilities can make any investment appear attractive.

### Stress Testing

Stress testing examines how the portfolio behaves under severe conditions.

Possible tests include:

Core assets fall fifty percent

Speculative assets fall ninety percent

A stablecoin depegs

An exchange freezes withdrawals

A DeFi protocol is exploited

A Layer 2 bridge fails

Network fees rise dramatically

Income is lost

Tax becomes payable during a bear market

Ask:

What is the total loss?

Can essential obligations still be met?

Which positions share the same risk?

Can assets be accessed?

Which actions would be required?

A portfolio should be survivable under more than the optimistic scenario.

### Drawdown Planning

A drawdown is a decline from the portfolio’s previous peak.

The investor should estimate how they would respond to:

Twenty-percent drawdown

Forty-percent drawdown

Sixty-percent drawdown

Eighty-percent drawdown

The plan may specify:

No emotional selling without thesis review

No increased leverage

Reassess asset quality

Rebalance only when criteria remain satisfied

Preserve emergency liquidity

The purpose is to prepare before the emotional event occurs.

### Bear-Market Plan

A bear-market plan may include:

Reviewing every thesis

Eliminating weak or fraudulent assets

Reducing unnecessary platform exposure

Monitoring token unlocks

Preserving liquidity

Avoiding forced yield strategies

Maintaining security

Continuing only predefined accumulation plans

Updating tax records

A bear market can reveal which projects depend on incentives and speculation.

Falling price does not automatically mean every asset is attractive.

### Bull-Market Plan

A bull-market plan may include:

Rebalancing oversized positions

Reducing speculative concentration

Taking staged profits

Avoiding excessive leverage

Reviewing valuation

Strengthening custody

Preparing for tax obligations

Resisting FOMO

Rising markets create a different form of risk: overconfidence.

A framework should protect capital during both fear and euphoria.

### Market-Cycle Awareness

Cryptocurrency markets often move through phases involving:

Accumulation

Trend development

Euphoria

Distribution

Decline

Capitulation

Recovery

Cycle identification is uncertain.

The framework should not require perfect timing.

Instead, it may adjust:

Position size

Profit-taking

Speculative exposure

Liquidity reserve

Research standards

Market-cycle awareness should support risk management rather than absolute prediction.

### Review Schedule

A portfolio-review schedule may include:

### Monthly Operational Review

Custody

Transactions

DeFi positions

Security alerts

Liquidation risk

### Quarterly Investment Review

Allocation

Thesis

Adoption

Tokenomics

Valuation

Rebalancing

### Annual Policy Review

Financial objectives

Risk capacity

Tax

Regulation

Portfolio limits

Custody plan

Event-driven reviews should occur after material developments.

### Material Events

Events that may trigger immediate review include:

Security exploit

Stablecoin depeg

Exchange insolvency concern

Founder departure

Major governance proposal

Token-supply change

Unexpected unlock

Regulatory action

Network outage

Bridge failure

Loss of important integration

Not every social-media rumour deserves immediate action.

Material events should be verified through credible sources.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',8,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
