INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-05-lesson-06','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Monitoring Frequency and Reviewing Timeframe Errors','cmf-module-3-05','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Monitoring Frequency and Reviewing Timeframe Errors, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Monitoring Frequency

The position should be monitored according to its timeframe.

A weekly investment does not need to be reviewed every minute.

Constantly watching lower-timeframe price changes can create emotional interference.

A leveraged intraday position requires more active monitoring because liquidation and volatility risks are immediate.

The plan should state when the position will be reviewed, such as at the close of each decision-timeframe candle.

### Alerts

Price and indicator alerts can reduce unnecessary chart watching.

An alert may be set near:

Entry area

Invalidation

Target

Major structural level

Volatility threshold

Alerts support discipline, but they should be configured carefully.

A notification should trigger review rather than automatic emotional action unless the strategy is explicitly automated.

### Trade Management

Trade management begins after entry.

A well-designed plan should minimise discretionary decisions during the position.

The participant should know in advance whether:

Stops may be moved

Additions are permitted

Partial profits will be taken

A time stop applies

The position may remain open through major events

The strategy permits overnight or weekend exposure

Unplanned management usually reflects emotion rather than new evidence.

### Moving the Stop

A stop may be adjusted only according to predefined rules.

Possible methods include:

Moving below a new higher low

Trailing by ATR

Moving to break even after a defined profit

Following a moving average

Tightening near major resistance

Moving the stop farther away increases risk and generally violates the original plan.

Moving it too quickly toward the entry may remove the position during normal volatility.

The market does not recognise the trader’s break-even price as a technical level.

### Adding to the Position

Additional entries should be planned.

A trend strategy may permit pyramiding after price confirms continuation.

A staged investment may allow purchases at several predefined levels.

The plan should define:

Maximum total size

Conditions for each addition

Revised average price

New total risk

Updated invalidation

An addition should not cause the total loss at the stop to exceed the portfolio risk limit.

### Reducing the Position

Reduction may occur when:

First target is reached

Position becomes too large

Momentum weakens

Higher-timeframe resistance approaches

Event risk increases

Portfolio correlation rises

A reduction is not necessarily a statement that the entire thesis has failed.

It may simply control risk.

### Event Management

Cryptocurrency markets operate continuously and can react sharply to scheduled and unscheduled events.

A trade plan should consider whether the position will remain open through:

Network upgrade

Token unlock

Governance vote

Economic announcement

Regulatory decision

Options expiry

Holding through an event may produce a large favourable movement.

It may also cause slippage beyond the planned stop.

The decision should be intentional.

### Overnight and Weekend Risk

Cryptocurrency trades continuously, but liquidity changes across hours and days.

A position may face weaker liquidity during periods when fewer institutions and market makers are active.

Spreads can widen and abnormal movements can occur more easily.

An intraday plan should specify whether positions may remain open beyond the intended session.

### Trade Cancellation

A pending plan should be cancelled when the evidence changes before entry.

For example, a bullish pullback setup may be invalidated when the higher-timeframe support breaks before the entry trigger occurs.

The participant should not continue waiting for the original signal simply because time was invested in the analysis.

A planned trade has no financial or emotional entitlement to be executed.

### Post-Trade Review

After the trade closes, evaluate the quality of the process.

The relevant questions are not limited to whether money was made.

Review whether:

Timeframes were selected appropriately

The higher-timeframe bias was clear

Entry matched the trigger

Position size was correct

Stop and target rules were followed

Any timeframe switching occurred

Actual costs differed from assumptions

The market regime changed

A profitable trade can contain poor decisions.

A losing trade can be correctly planned and executed.

### Trade Journal

A trade journal converts experience into evidence.

A useful entry should record the market, instrument, strategy and selected timeframes. It should include screenshots from the higher, decision and execution charts.

The journal should preserve the analysis as it existed before the outcome was known.

It can also record the participant’s emotional state. Fear, urgency, frustration and overconfidence can affect execution even when the technical plan is sound.

Over time, the journal may reveal that certain timeframe combinations, market regimes or entry methods perform better than others.

### Reviewing Timeframe Errors

Common timeframe errors include entering from a very low timeframe directly into major higher-timeframe resistance, placing the stop according to a chart too small for the thesis and managing a long-term position through short-term noise.

The journal should identify which timeframe controlled each decision.

If the answer changes after the trade begins, the process may be inconsistent.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',6,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
