INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-06-lesson-02','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Market Orders and Maker and Taker Orders','cmf-module-3-06','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Market Orders and Maker and Taker Orders, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Market Orders

A market order instructs the platform to execute immediately against the best available prices.

It prioritises execution over price.

A market buy consumes available sell orders.

A market sell consumes available buy orders.

Market orders may be useful when:

Immediate entry or exit is more important than precise price

The market is highly liquid

The position is small relative to available depth

A risk limit must be enforced quickly

Waiting creates greater risk than slippage

The participant does not control the final average execution price.

During rapid movement, the result may be substantially worse than the price visible when the order was submitted.

### Market-Order Slippage

Suppose the current ask is 50.

A participant submits a market order for 2,000 tokens.

Only 200 tokens are available near 50. The remainder executes progressively at 50.20, 50.50, 51 and higher.

The final average execution may be 51.10.

Expected price:

50

Actual average price:

51.10

Slippage:

1.10 units per token

On 2,000 tokens, this represents 2,200 units of additional cost before trading fees.

The market order succeeded operationally but may have damaged the trade’s expected value.

### When Market Orders Are Dangerous

Market orders are especially risky when:

The asset is illiquid

The order is large

The spread is wide

Volatility is expanding

A liquidation cascade is occurring

The exchange order book is shallow

Trading resumes after an outage

The token contains unusual transfer rules

The instruction effectively tells the market:

“Complete this transaction at the best prices currently available, regardless of how far those prices extend.”

That may be appropriate during an emergency exit.

It is rarely appropriate without first checking liquidity.

### Limit Orders

A limit order specifies the worst price the participant is willing to accept.

A buy limit sets the maximum purchase price.

A sell limit sets the minimum sale price.

Suppose an asset trades near 100.

A buy limit at 98 will execute only at 98 or lower.

A sell limit at 105 will execute only at 105 or higher.

Limit orders prioritise price control over execution certainty.

They may remain unfilled if the market never reaches the selected price.

### Passive and Marketable Limit Orders

A passive limit order is placed away from the current market and waits for another participant to trade against it.

For example, when the best bid is 99 and the best ask is 100, a buy limit at 98 is passive.

A marketable limit order crosses the spread but places a boundary on the worst acceptable price.

For example, a buy limit at 100.50 may immediately execute against sell orders up to 100.50 but refuse prices above it.

This can provide a balance between:

Fast execution

Protection from extreme slippage

A marketable limit order is often useful when urgency exists but unlimited price deterioration is unacceptable.

### Partial Fills

A limit order may execute only partially.

Suppose a participant submits a buy limit for 1,000 tokens at 20.

Only 300 tokens are sold at that price.

The result is:

300 tokens purchased

700 tokens still waiting

The participant must decide whether to:

Leave the remaining order active

Cancel it

Adjust the price

Enter the remainder elsewhere

Accept the smaller position

The trade plan should address partial fills before they occur.

A partially filled position may carry less risk than planned, but it can also create complications when stop and target orders are based on the full intended quantity.

### Queue Priority

Limit orders placed at the same price may execute according to queue priority.

The order submitted earlier may be filled before a later order at the same level.

Large quantities ahead in the queue can reduce the probability of execution.

Some exchanges may also use different matching rules.

A participant should not assume that price touching the limit guarantees a fill.

There must be sufficient opposing volume to reach that position in the queue.

### Maker and Taker Orders

A maker order adds liquidity to the order book.

A taker order removes existing liquidity.

A passive limit order generally acts as a maker.

A market order acts as a taker.

A marketable limit order may also act as a taker because it executes immediately against existing orders.

Platforms may apply different fee structures to makers and takers.

Maker fees may be lower because the order contributes liquidity.

Taker fees may be higher because the order demands immediate execution.

The fee difference should not determine the order type by itself.

Saving a small fee is not useful when the order misses a major movement or exposes the participant to uncontrolled risk.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',2,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-06-lesson-03','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Post-Only Orders and Trigger Prices','cmf-module-3-06','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Post-Only Orders and Trigger Prices, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Post-Only Orders

A post-only instruction ensures that an order is added to the order book rather than immediately executing as a taker.

If the order would cross the spread, the exchange may reject or adjust it according to platform rules.

Post-only orders are useful when:

The participant wants maker execution

Fee control matters

Immediate execution is unnecessary

The strategy depends on passive liquidity provision

The risk is non-execution.

The market may move away before the order fills.

### Time-in-Force Instructions

Time-in-force determines how long an order remains active and how it may execute.

Availability and exact behaviour vary between platforms.

### Good-Till-Cancelled

A good-till-cancelled order, commonly abbreviated as GTC, remains active until:

It executes

The participant cancels it

The platform removes it under specified conditions

GTC orders are useful for planned entries or exits that may take time.

They also create forgotten-order risk.

An old order may execute after market conditions or the investment thesis have changed.

Open orders should be reviewed regularly.

### Immediate-or-Cancel

An immediate-or-cancel order, or IOC, attempts to execute immediately.

Any quantity that cannot execute at once within the price conditions is cancelled.

Suppose an IOC buy order requests 1,000 tokens at no more than 50.

If 600 tokens are available, those 600 may execute and the remaining 400 are cancelled.

IOC can be useful when partial execution is acceptable but waiting is not.

### Fill-or-Kill

A fill-or-kill order, or FOK, must execute the entire requested quantity immediately or be cancelled completely.

It avoids partial fills.

This may be useful when:

The strategy requires the complete position

Partial exposure creates undesirable risk

Several transaction legs must remain balanced

FOK orders may fail frequently when the market lacks sufficient depth.

### Day and Expiry Orders

Some platforms allow an order to expire at a specified time.

This reduces the risk of old orders remaining active after their strategic purpose has ended.

In continuous cryptocurrency markets, “day” boundaries may depend on the exchange’s time standard.

The participant should verify the precise expiry time.

### Stop Orders

A stop order becomes active only after a trigger price is reached.

It is commonly used for:

Risk control

Breakout entry

Trend confirmation

Conditional execution

The trigger price is not necessarily the execution price.

This distinction is critical.

A stop order is an instruction to create another order when the market reaches a specified condition.

### Stop-Market Orders

A stop-market order becomes a market order after the stop price is triggered.

Suppose a participant owns an asset at 100 and sets a sell stop at 92.

When the trigger condition is reached, the platform submits a market sell order.

The advantage is that the order prioritises closing the position.

The disadvantage is that execution may occur below 92.

During a rapid decline, the average fill might be 90, 87 or lower.

The stop defines the trigger, not the guaranteed exit price.

### Stop-Limit Orders

A stop-limit order creates a limit order after the stop price is triggered.

Suppose:

Stop trigger: 92

Sell limit: 91

When price reaches the trigger, the exchange submits a sell limit at 91.

The order can execute at 91 or higher.

It will not sell below 91.

This controls the minimum price.

It also creates the risk that the position remains open if the market moves directly below 91.

A stop-limit order provides price protection but not exit certainty.

### Stop-Market Versus Stop-Limit

A stop-market order asks:

How can I leave the position as quickly as possible after invalidation?

A stop-limit order asks:

How can I avoid selling below a specified price?

During ordinary liquid conditions, either may work as expected.

During a fast market, the difference becomes significant.

For risk exits, non-execution may be more damaging than slippage. In other situations, such as a thin temporary wick, accepting any price may be undesirable.

The order type should reflect which risk matters more.

### Trigger Prices

Derivative platforms may allow stops to be triggered by different price references.

These may include:

Last traded price

Mark price

Index price

The last traded price reflects the latest exchange transaction.

The index price may combine external spot-market prices.

The mark price is often designed to estimate a fair contract value and reduce unnecessary liquidations caused by temporary exchange-specific movement.

A stop triggered by one price reference may behave differently from a liquidation mechanism using another.

The participant should know exactly which price controls each instruction.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',3,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-06-lesson-04','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Buy-Stop Entries and Close-Position Instructions','cmf-module-3-06','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Buy-Stop Entries and Close-Position Instructions, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Buy-Stop Entries

A buy stop is placed above the current market price.

It may be used to enter after bullish confirmation.

Suppose resistance is at 100 and the participant wants to enter only if price moves above 102.

A buy-stop order can trigger at 102.

If it becomes a market order, the final fill may be higher.

A buy stop can automate breakout participation.

It can also be triggered by a brief liquidity sweep and produce a poor entry.

### Sell-Stop Entries

A sell stop is placed below the current market price.

It may be used to enter a bearish position after support breaks.

As with a buy stop, the market may move rapidly after the trigger.

The trader should consider:

Liquidity

Slippage

Derivative funding

Borrow availability

Stop distance

A breakdown order does not confirm that the new trend will persist.

### Trailing Stops

A trailing stop adjusts as price moves favourably.

For a long position, the stop rises as the market reaches higher prices.

For a short position, the stop moves downward as price falls.

The trailing distance may be defined as:

Fixed amount

Percentage

ATR multiple

Structural level

Indicator value

Suppose a long position uses a ten-percent trailing stop.

If price rises from 100 to 150, the trailing reference may move to approximately 135.

If price then falls to the trigger, an exit order is submitted.

### Advantages and Limitations of Trailing Stops

A trailing stop can help:

Protect part of a gain

Remain in a trend

Reduce emotional exit decisions

It cannot:

Identify the exact market top

Guarantee execution at the trigger

Distinguish normal volatility from reversal

Prevent slippage

A trailing distance that is too tight creates frequent premature exits.

A distance that is too wide gives back a large part of the unrealised gain.

The distance should match the asset’s volatility and the strategy’s timeframe.

### Exchange-Managed and Strategy-Managed Trailing Stops

Some platforms provide automatic trailing-stop orders.

A participant may instead update a conventional stop according to a written strategy.

The first method reduces manual work but depends on the exchange’s order system.

The second allows greater flexibility but increases operational and behavioural risk.

A manually managed stop is only useful if the participant follows the rule consistently.

### Bracket Orders

A bracket order surrounds a position with an intended profit exit and a protective stop.

For a long position, the bracket may include:

Buy entry

Sell target above

Sell stop below

The target and stop are linked to the position.

When one exit executes, the other should normally be cancelled.

Bracket orders help translate the complete trade plan into market instructions.

Their exact implementation varies by platform.

The participant should verify whether the platform automatically adjusts quantities after partial fills.

### One-Cancels-the-Other Orders

A one-cancels-the-other order, or OCO, links two orders.

When one executes, the other is cancelled.

A common use is combining:

Profit-taking limit order

Protective stop order

Suppose an asset is purchased at 100.

The participant places:

Sell limit at 120

Sell stop at 92

If the target fills, the stop is cancelled.

If the stop fills, the target is cancelled.

Without this linkage, both orders might remain active and create an unintended position later.

### One-Triggers-the-Other Orders

A one-triggers-the-other instruction activates a second order only after the first order executes.

For example:

Entry limit order fills

Protective stop becomes active

Profit target becomes active

This can prevent exit orders from operating before the position exists.

Participants should understand how partial entry fills affect the linked orders.

### Reduce-Only Orders

A reduce-only instruction ensures that an order can reduce or close an existing derivative position but cannot increase it or open a position in the opposite direction.

Suppose a trader holds a long position of ten contracts.

A reduce-only sell order can close some or all of those contracts.

It should not create a short position if the long has already been closed elsewhere.

Reduce-only instructions are important when several exit orders exist.

Without them, a target or stop remaining active after closure may accidentally create a new position.

### Close-Position Instructions

Some platforms provide a close-position instruction that attempts to close the entire current position when triggered.

This can simplify exits when the quantity changes because of partial reductions.

The participant should verify whether it:

Uses market or limit execution

Applies reduce-only behaviour

Cancels other orders

Uses last, mark or index price as the trigger

Platform terminology can appear similar while producing different results.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',4,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
