INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-09-lesson-07','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Correlation and Options and Margin and Multi-Leg Positions','cmf-module-3-09','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Correlation and Options and Margin and Multi-Leg Positions, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Correlation and Options

Portfolio volatility depends on both individual asset volatility and correlation.

When correlations rise, a diversified portfolio can experience larger combined movement.

Index option pricing may reflect expected correlation among components.

During crises, correlations often increase.

An option hedge designed using ordinary correlation may provide insufficient protection when all assets decline together.

### Volatility Trading Without Direction

A trader can attempt to isolate volatility by hedging delta.

For example, a long straddle may be adjusted regularly to remain approximately delta neutral.

The trader then seeks to benefit from realised movement relative to option cost.

This does not remove all directional risk.

Delta changes continuously, hedges occur with delay and markets can gap.

The position also remains exposed to theta, vega, liquidity and model error.

### Volatility Carry

A short-volatility trader may attempt to collect the difference between implied and realised volatility.

The trade may produce regular gains when markets remain stable.

The risk appears when realised volatility suddenly exceeds expectations.

A robust volatility-carry strategy should account for:

Tail hedges

Position limits

Volatility regime

Liquidity

Margin expansion

Correlation shock

Selling volatility without a tail-risk framework can create hidden leverage.

### Volatility Regime Selection

Option strategy should match the volatility environment.

When implied volatility is low relative to expected future movement, long-volatility structures may be attractive.

When implied volatility is very high and the participant believes actual movement will be smaller, defined-risk short-volatility structures may be considered.

The labels “high” and “low” must be relative to:

The asset’s history

Upcoming events

Realised volatility

Other expiries

Other strikes

Low implied volatility can fall further. High implied volatility can become much higher.

### Direction and Volatility Together

An option thesis should specify both direction and volatility where relevant.

A trader can be:

Bullish and long volatility

Bullish and short volatility

Bearish and long volatility

Bearish and short volatility

Direction neutral and long volatility

Direction neutral and short volatility

A long call is bullish and generally long volatility.

A bull put spread is bullish but generally short volatility.

The same directional opinion can therefore be expressed through very different risk profiles.

### Strategy Selection Example

Suppose a trader expects a moderate rise and believes implied volatility is expensive.

Buying a call may overpay for volatility.

A bull call spread reduces the premium and vega exposure while capping upside.

A bull put spread earns premium but accepts downside risk.

A covered call may suit an investor already holding the asset but caps gains.

The “best” strategy depends on more than bullishness.

It depends on expected magnitude, volatility, time and loss tolerance.

### Options Around Breakouts

A trader expecting a breakout may buy a straddle or strangle.

The position can benefit from movement in either direction.

However, implied volatility often rises before a widely observed breakout.

The options may already price a substantial move.

If the eventual breakout is smaller than expected, both options can lose value.

A cheaper alternative may use a directional spread after confirmation, accepting the risk of entering later.

### Options Around Mean Reversion

A trader expecting price to remain inside a range may consider a defined-risk short-volatility strategy such as an iron condor.

The strategy earns premium while price remains between the short strikes.

If the range breaks, losses can develop quickly.

The option structure should be closed or managed according to the regime invalidation rather than held merely because time decay remains positive.

### Options for Trend Following

A long-dated call can provide trend exposure with premium-defined risk.

A call spread can reduce cost while capping profit.

A trader can also use a trailing exit on the option or underlying asset.

The expiry must provide enough time for the trend to develop.

Repeatedly buying short-dated calls within a long-term trend can produce large cumulative theta losses.

### Options for Hedging Leveraged Positions

A futures trader may buy an option to limit extreme loss.

For example, a leveraged long futures position can be paired with a put.

The put may gain during a severe decline.

However, the futures position can still be liquidated before the option hedge is monetised unless margin and execution are managed correctly.

The hedge must be sized, accessible and held on a platform capable of honouring it.

### Margin and Multi-Leg Positions

Platforms may recognise the offsetting risk of multi-leg strategies and reduce margin requirements.

A call spread requires less margin than a naked short call because the purchased call limits maximum loss.

Margin treatment depends on:

Platform model

Contract settlement

Strike relationship

Expiry

Portfolio margin rules

A platform error, leg mismatch or early assignment can temporarily remove the hedge.

The trader should understand the risk of each leg independently and as a combination.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',7,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
