INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-09-lesson-08','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Legging Risk and Scenario Grid','cmf-module-3-09','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Legging Risk and Scenario Grid, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Legging Risk

Legging risk occurs when the components of a multi-leg strategy are not executed simultaneously.

Suppose a trader intends to create a call spread.

They buy the first call. Before selling the second call, the market moves and the premium changes.

The final spread cost becomes worse than expected.

On exit, one leg may fill while the other remains open.

The trader is temporarily exposed to a different risk profile.

Complex orders should use combined spread execution where sufficiently liquid.

### Assignment Risk in Multi-Leg Strategies

American-style short options can be assigned before expiry.

If one leg of a spread is assigned while the protective leg remains open, the trader may acquire an unintended underlying or short position.

European-style cash-settled contracts reduce early-assignment complexity but retain settlement risk.

The participant must understand whether assignment is possible and how the platform handles it.

### Liquidity Across Legs

A strategy is only as executable as its least liquid leg.

A four-leg iron condor may show an attractive theoretical payoff.

If one wing has a very wide spread, entry and exit costs may consume much of the premium.

The participant should examine:

Bid and ask for each leg

Combined spread quote

Available quantity

Open interest

Expected slippage

Complexity can multiply trading costs.

### Closing Before Expiry

Multi-leg positions do not need to be held until expiry.

A trader may close when:

A percentage of maximum profit is achieved

Implied volatility changes

The market regime changes

Risk increases near expiry

The original thesis is invalidated

Liquidity remains adequate

Waiting for the final small portion of potential profit can expose the position to disproportionate gamma risk.

### Managing Short-Volatility Positions

A short-volatility position can be managed by:

Closing at a predefined profit

Closing after a loss threshold

Reducing size when volatility rises

Buying additional protection

Rolling the threatened side

Closing the entire structure

Rolling a losing option does not remove the loss.

It realises the existing position and creates a new one.

The new structure should be evaluated independently.

### Rolling Spreads

A spread may be rolled to:

Later expiry

Different strikes

Both

A credit may be received during the roll, but the trader may also widen the period of risk or increase maximum loss.

The relevant calculation is not whether the roll produces a credit.

It is the combined realised loss, new exposure and remaining maximum risk.

### Early Profit-Taking

Short premium strategies often close after earning part of the maximum possible credit.

For example, a trader may close after capturing half the premium.

This reduces the time during which the strategy remains exposed to a sudden adverse move.

It also gives up remaining theta income.

The rule should be based on tested strategy behaviour rather than an arbitrary desire to avoid discomfort.

### Stop-Losses on Spreads

Spread prices may have wide or unstable quotes.

A stop based on the spread’s displayed price can trigger on poor market data.

Some traders manage the position according to:

Underlying price

Short strike

Delta

Maximum loss percentage

Market regime

Implied volatility

The maximum possible loss should remain acceptable even if the planned exit cannot be executed at the desired price.

### Pin and Expiry Risk

As expiry approaches, a multi-leg position can change rapidly when the underlying trades near one of its strikes.

A small movement may cause:

Delta shift

Assignment

Exercise

Sudden profit change

Large hedge requirement

Closing before expiry can reduce this operational uncertainty.

The cost is surrendering remaining time value or paying the spread.

### Options Position Sizing

Long options should be sized assuming the premium can be lost completely.

Defined-risk spreads should be sized using their maximum loss rather than the credit received.

Short uncovered options require stress testing far beyond ordinary historical movements.

A portfolio should also aggregate exposures across strategies.

Several positions may all be:

Long delta

Short volatility

Concentrated in one expiry

Dependent on one exchange

Collateralised by one stablecoin

The number of strategy names does not determine diversification.

### Greek Exposure at Portfolio Level

An option portfolio may be summarised through net Greeks.

A portfolio could have:

Positive delta

Negative gamma

Positive theta

Negative vega

This might describe a bullish premium-selling portfolio.

It benefits from moderate upward movement and time decay but may lose during a sharp move or volatility increase.

Net Greeks provide a snapshot.

Because the Greeks change, stress scenarios are still required.

### Scenario Grid

A scenario grid estimates the portfolio value under combinations of:

Underlying price movement

Implied-volatility change

Passage of time

For example, a trader may calculate the position after:

Price falls ten percent

Price remains unchanged

Price rises ten percent

combined with:

IV falls ten points

IV remains unchanged

IV rises ten points

This reveals risks hidden by an expiry payoff diagram.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',8,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
