INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-10-lesson-01','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Derivatives Positioning and Price Rising With Open Interest Rising','cmf-module-3-10','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Derivatives Positioning and Price Rising With Open Interest Rising, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Learning Objectives

By the end of this module, you should understand how derivatives data can reveal the positioning, leverage and vulnerability behind cryptocurrency price movements.

You should be able to interpret open interest, funding rates, futures basis, trading volume and liquidation data together rather than treating them as isolated signals. You should also understand how short squeezes, long squeezes and deleveraging events develop, why crowded positioning can persist longer than expected and how derivatives activity can influence spot markets.

Most importantly, you should be able to distinguish between evidence and inference. Derivatives data can suggest what market participants may be doing, but it rarely reveals their exact intentions or identifies a market turning point with certainty.

### Introduction

A price chart shows what the market has done.

Derivatives data can provide additional insight into how that movement may have been financed and which participants may be vulnerable if price changes direction.

Suppose Bitcoin rises by ten percent.

The price increase alone does not explain whether the movement was driven by genuine spot demand, new leveraged long positions, short sellers being forced to close or a combination of these forces.

Those distinctions matter.

A rally supported by sustained spot buying and moderate leverage may be more stable than one driven mainly by short liquidations and rapidly increasing speculative exposure.

Similarly, a market decline can result from genuine selling, new short positions, forced liquidation of leveraged longs or the withdrawal of liquidity.

Derivatives analysis attempts to examine these underlying forces.

Commonly used measures include open interest, funding rates, futures basis, volume, long-short ratios and liquidation estimates.

No single measure is sufficient.

High open interest is not automatically bullish or bearish. Positive funding does not prove that price must fall. A large liquidation event does not guarantee that the market has reached a bottom or top.

The value comes from combining several measures with price structure, spot activity, market regime and liquidity.

### Derivatives Positioning

Derivatives positioning refers to the exposure held through futures, perpetual contracts, options and related instruments.

Every futures or perpetual contract contains both a long and a short side.

One participant gains when the contract price rises, while the other benefits when it falls.

This means the existence of a large number of contracts does not reveal which side is “correct.”

It reveals that a large amount of exposure exists.

The market becomes especially important when those positions use leverage.

Leverage creates thresholds at which participants may be forced to reduce or close exposure. Once those thresholds are reached, ordinary trading decisions become involuntary transactions.

A trader may want to hold a long position, but the exchange’s liquidation system may sell it automatically.

These forced orders can accelerate price movement and create feedback loops.

### Open Interest

Open interest measures the total number or notional value of derivative contracts that remain open.

It increases when new positions are created and decreases when positions are closed, expire or are liquidated.

Suppose one trader opens a new long futures position and another trader opens the corresponding short.

Open interest increases because a new contract now exists.

If those traders later close the contract, open interest decreases.

Open interest is different from trading volume.

Volume measures how much trading occurred during a period. Open interest measures how much exposure remains outstanding after that trading.

A market can have high volume with little change in open interest if positions are changing hands rapidly.

It can also have steadily increasing open interest without unusually high short-term volume if participants build exposure gradually.

### Why Open Interest Matters

Open interest provides information about the amount of capital and leverage committed to the derivatives market.

Rising open interest can indicate that new positions are entering.

Falling open interest can indicate that positions are being closed or liquidated.

The measure becomes more useful when combined with price.

The interaction between price and open interest can suggest whether a move is supported by new exposure or driven by the removal of existing positions.

These are interpretations, not definitive conclusions.

Every contract still contains both a long and a short participant, and their motivations may differ.

### Price Rising With Open Interest Rising

When price and open interest rise together, new derivative positions are entering while the market moves upward.

This may indicate growing speculative participation.

Possible explanations include new leveraged longs, hedged institutional activity, market-making positions or traders entering both sides at higher prices.

The most common interpretation is that fresh capital is supporting the trend.

This can strengthen momentum.

It can also make the market more fragile.

If the new exposure is highly leveraged and concentrated on the long side, a later decline may trigger liquidations.

The analyst should therefore examine funding rates, basis and spot volume before concluding that rising open interest confirms a healthy rally.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',1,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-10-lesson-02','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Price Rising With Open Interest Falling and Interpreting Negative Funding','cmf-module-3-10','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Price Rising With Open Interest Falling and Interpreting Negative Funding, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Price Rising With Open Interest Falling

When price rises while open interest declines, existing positions are being closed as the market moves upward.

One possible explanation is short covering.

Short traders buy contracts or underlying exposure to close their positions. Their buying pushes price higher while open interest falls.

This can produce a short squeeze.

A short-covering rally may be extremely powerful, but it may weaken when most vulnerable shorts have already exited.

If the market is to continue rising, new spot demand or new long participation may eventually need to replace the forced buying.

Falling open interest during a rally is therefore neither automatically bullish nor bearish. It suggests that position removal is contributing to the move.

### Price Falling With Open Interest Rising

When price declines while open interest increases, new exposure is entering during the fall.

This may indicate new short positions, hedging activity or traders attempting to buy the decline through leveraged longs.

Funding rates and basis can help distinguish between these possibilities.

If funding becomes increasingly negative, short demand may be dominant.

If funding remains strongly positive despite falling price, leveraged longs may still be crowded and vulnerable.

A decline with rising open interest can continue because new positions are reinforcing the movement.

It can also create conditions for a later squeeze if one side becomes excessively concentrated.

### Price Falling With Open Interest Falling

When both price and open interest decline, positions are leaving the market.

This often occurs during long liquidation or broad deleveraging.

Leveraged long positions are closed voluntarily or forcibly, reducing open interest while adding selling pressure.

The movement can be severe because liquidations create immediate market orders.

Once the excessive leverage has been removed, the market may stabilise.

However, falling open interest does not prove that the decline is complete.

Spot holders may continue selling even after derivatives leverage has been reduced.

### Open Interest in Monetary Terms

Open interest may be reported as:

Number of contracts

Number of underlying tokens

National-currency value

Stablecoin value

The selected unit can change the interpretation.

Suppose the number of open contracts remains constant while Bitcoin’s price doubles.

Open interest measured in currency value also doubles even though no new contracts were created.

Analysts should therefore check whether changes result from new positions or simply from price movement.

Comparing open interest in both token and currency terms can provide a clearer picture.

### Open Interest Relative to Market Size

A large open-interest figure should be evaluated relative to:

Spot-market volume

Market capitalisation

Exchange liquidity

Historical open interest

Realised volatility

One billion units of open interest may be modest for a very large asset and extreme for a smaller token.

A useful question is not simply whether open interest is high.

It is whether open interest is unusually high relative to the market’s capacity to absorb forced transactions.

### Open-Interest Concentration

Total open interest may be distributed across several exchanges and contracts.

Concentration on one platform creates additional risk.

An exchange outage, liquidation-engine failure or local price distortion can affect a large portion of the market.

Open interest may also concentrate in one expiry or strike area.

This can influence market behaviour near settlement.

A complete analysis should examine where the exposure exists, not only its aggregate value.

### Funding Rates

Funding rates are periodic payments exchanged between long and short holders of perpetual contracts.

Their purpose is to encourage the perpetual price to remain near the spot or index price.

When perpetual contracts trade above the reference market, funding is often positive.

Long positions pay short positions.

When perpetuals trade below the reference price, funding may become negative.

Short positions then pay longs.

Funding provides information about the relative demand for leveraged exposure.

It does not directly predict future price.

### Interpreting Positive Funding

Positive funding generally indicates that traders are willing to pay to maintain long perpetual exposure.

A moderately positive funding rate can be normal during a healthy bullish market.

It may reflect strong demand without being excessive.

As funding rises, the cost of holding long exposure increases.

Very high positive funding may indicate:

Crowded longs

Speculative optimism

Perpetual price trading above spot

Increased liquidation vulnerability

Demand for short-side funding income

Extreme positive funding is a warning that the long side may be crowded.

It is not an automatic short signal.

Price can continue rising while positive funding remains elevated.

### Interpreting Negative Funding

Negative funding indicates strong demand for short perpetual exposure or a perpetual price below its reference market.

Shorts pay longs.

This may occur during bearish sentiment, panic or aggressive hedging.

Very negative funding can indicate crowded short positioning.

The market may become vulnerable to a short squeeze if price begins rising.

However, negative funding can remain in place during a persistent bear trend.

Receiving funding does not compensate for a large directional loss.

A long position entered only because funding is negative may still lose substantially if price continues falling.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',2,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-10-lesson-03','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Funding as a Cost of Carry and The Relationship Between Spot and Derivatives','cmf-module-3-10','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Funding as a Cost of Carry and The Relationship Between Spot and Derivatives, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Funding as a Cost of Carry

Funding affects the economics of holding a perpetual position.

Suppose a trader holds a long position with notional exposure of 100,000 units.

If funding is 0.02 percent for the interval, the payment is:

100,000 × 0.02 percent = 20 units

If several funding intervals occur each day, the cost can accumulate.

For a highly leveraged trader, funding may represent a meaningful percentage of the margin committed.

A strategy should estimate the possible funding cost across the expected holding period.

The current funding rate may change, so scenario analysis is more useful than assuming one fixed rate.

### Annualising Funding

Funding rates are sometimes converted into annualised figures.

This can make small periodic rates appear extremely large.

Suppose a funding rate is 0.01 percent every eight hours.

There are three intervals per day.

A simple annualised estimate is:

0.01 percent × 3 × 365 = 10.95 percent

This assumes the funding rate remains constant for an entire year.

In reality, funding changes continuously and can reverse.

Annualised funding is a comparison tool, not a promised return or cost.

### Funding Rate Versus Funding Payment

The funding rate is the percentage applied.

The funding payment is the actual amount transferred.

A small rate applied to a very large position can produce a large payment.

A high rate applied to a small position may remain financially limited.

Analysis should therefore consider both the percentage and the notional exposure affected.

### Predicted Funding

Many platforms display a predicted rate for the next funding interval.

This value may change before settlement because it depends on the evolving premium between the perpetual and reference market.

A trader should not assume the displayed estimate is final.

Funding strategies based on one predicted payment can be overwhelmed by ordinary price movement or a last-minute rate adjustment.

### Funding Across Exchanges

Funding rates can differ between exchanges.

One venue may have strongly positive funding while another remains neutral.

This can occur because of different participants, collateral, liquidity and contract design.

Professional traders may arbitrage these differences by taking opposite positions across venues.

The apparent opportunity carries:

Exchange counterparty risk

Transfer risk

Margin risk

Execution mismatch

Different index methodology

Funding reversal

A funding difference is not risk-free income.

### Futures Basis

Futures basis is the difference between a futures price and the underlying spot price.

When futures trade above spot, the market is in contango.

When futures trade below spot, it is in backwardation.

Basis can reveal demand for leverage, financing conditions and market stress.

A strongly positive basis often accompanies bullish markets.

A negative basis may occur during panic, hedging demand or immediate spot scarcity.

Basis should be examined across expiries to understand the complete futures curve.

### Perpetual Premium

Perpetual contracts do not have an expiry-based basis in the same way as dated futures.

However, they can trade at a premium or discount to the reference index.

The funding mechanism responds to this difference.

A persistent premium suggests strong demand for long perpetual exposure.

A persistent discount suggests stronger short demand.

The premium can change rapidly during liquidations or exchange-specific stress.

### Basis and Funding Together

Funding and basis often provide complementary information.

A bullish market with moderate positive basis and moderate positive funding may indicate healthy demand.

A market with extreme basis, extreme funding and rapidly rising open interest may indicate speculative leverage.

A falling market with negative basis and deeply negative funding may reflect strong bearish positioning.

If open interest is also high, the market may be vulnerable to a squeeze.

The interpretation should focus on the combined structure rather than one threshold.

### Spot-Led and Derivatives-Led Moves

One important analytical question is whether spot or derivatives activity appears to be leading price.

A spot-led rally may show strong buying on major spot exchanges, improving market depth and moderate derivatives leverage.

A derivatives-led rally may show rapid open-interest growth, rising funding and aggressive perpetual-market volume without equivalent spot demand.

The second structure can still continue.

It is more dependent on leverage and therefore potentially more vulnerable to forced unwinding.

A spot-led decline may reflect genuine asset selling.

A derivatives-led decline may result mainly from liquidation or new short exposure.

### The Relationship Between Spot and Derivatives

Spot and derivatives markets influence one another through arbitrage.

If a futures or perpetual contract trades significantly above spot, arbitrage traders may buy spot and sell the derivative.

If the derivative trades below spot, they may take the opposite exposure where practical.

These activities help keep prices aligned.

During stress, arbitrage can weaken because of:

Capital constraints

Exchange risk

Withdrawal delays

Borrowing limits

Stablecoin concerns

Liquidation risk

The relationship can therefore diverge temporarily.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',3,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-10-lesson-04','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Liquidations and Leverage Rebuilding','cmf-module-3-10','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Liquidations and Leverage Rebuilding, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Liquidations

Liquidation occurs when a leveraged position no longer has sufficient margin to remain open.

The platform closes the position automatically.

A liquidated long position produces selling.

A liquidated short produces buying.

Liquidation data attempts to estimate or record these forced closures.

It can reveal where leverage is being removed from the market.

Liquidation figures vary between data providers because exchanges differ in transparency and reporting methods.

They should be treated as estimates unless the underlying source is clearly known.

### Long Liquidations

Long liquidations occur when falling prices force leveraged long positions to close.

These liquidations add market sell orders to an already declining market.

A feedback loop can develop:

Price falls.

Long positions lose margin.

Liquidations create additional selling.

Price falls further.

More longs are liquidated.

This is a long squeeze or downward liquidation cascade.

The process can push price far below levels suggested by ordinary supply and demand.

### Short Liquidations

Short liquidations occur when rising prices force short positions to close.

Closing a short requires buying.

This forced buying accelerates the rise.

As price increases, more short positions reach their liquidation thresholds.

The cycle can create a short squeeze.

Short squeezes are especially powerful when:

Open interest is high

Funding is negative

Price breaks major resistance

Spot liquidity is limited

Short positioning is concentrated

A squeeze can continue until the vulnerable short exposure has been removed.

### Liquidation Cascades

A liquidation cascade is not simply a large price move.

It is a self-reinforcing process in which price movement triggers forced transactions that create further movement.

The speed of the cascade depends on:

Amount of leverage

Distribution of liquidation prices

Order-book depth

Exchange liquidation rules

Market-maker capacity

Cross-exchange arbitrage

When several platforms liquidate similar positions simultaneously, price can move rapidly across the entire market.

### Estimated Liquidation Levels

Some analytical platforms estimate where large groups of leveraged positions may be liquidated.

These estimates may be displayed as heatmaps or clusters.

They can help identify areas where forced transactions might increase.

However, liquidation estimates are uncertain because analysts may not know:

Exact entry prices

Margin added

Cross versus isolated margin

Platform maintenance requirements

Hedge positions

Position changes

Collateral value

A liquidation heatmap is a model, not a map of guaranteed future orders.

### Liquidation Levels as Potential Liquidity

Markets may move toward areas containing large concentrations of stop orders and liquidation thresholds.

These areas contain potential future transactions.

A cluster of short liquidations above price may create buying if reached.

A cluster of long liquidations below price may create selling.

This does not mean the market is deliberately controlled by one entity seeking every cluster.

Many participants respond to the same visible structure, creating natural concentrations of orders.

The presence of potential liquidity can influence market behaviour without determining direction.

### Liquidation Data and Reversals

A large liquidation event can precede a reversal because excessive leverage has been removed.

For example, after a severe long-liquidation cascade:

Open interest may collapse

Funding may reset

Forced selling may decline

Spot buyers may enter

Price may recover

This does not guarantee a durable bottom.

The market can experience several liquidation waves during a broader downtrend.

The analyst should look for stabilisation in price structure and spot demand rather than assuming that one large liquidation total marks the end.

### Liquidation Data and Continuation

Liquidations can also support continuation.

Suppose price breaks major support and liquidates longs.

If spot sellers remain active and new shorts enter, the decline can continue after the first cascade.

Similarly, a short squeeze may develop into a sustainable rally if genuine buying replaces forced short covering.

The key question is what happens after the forced flow weakens.

Does independent demand or supply remain?

### Deleveraging

Deleveraging is the reduction of borrowed or leveraged exposure.

It can occur gradually through voluntary position closure or suddenly through liquidation.

A deleveraging event often produces:

Falling open interest

High derivatives volume

Large liquidations

Funding normalisation

Rapid price movement

Deleveraging can improve the market’s structural health by removing fragile exposure.

It can also cause severe short-term losses.

A market with lower leverage after a cascade may be more stable, but stability still depends on spot-market behaviour and liquidity.

### Leverage Rebuilding

After deleveraging, open interest may begin rising again.

The quality of the recovery depends on how quickly and in which direction leverage rebuilds.

A gradual increase alongside spot demand may support a healthy trend.

A rapid return of extreme leverage can recreate the same vulnerability that caused the previous cascade.

Funding, basis and spot volume should be monitored during the rebuilding process.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',4,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-10-lesson-05','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Long-Short Ratios and Put-Call Ratios','cmf-module-3-10','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Long-Short Ratios and Put-Call Ratios, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Long-Short Ratios

Long-short ratios attempt to compare bullish and bearish positioning.

The ratio may be based on:

Number of accounts

Position notional

Selected professional traders

Top accounts

One exchange’s users

These measures can be misleading.

A hundred small long accounts may be offset by one large short position.

A trader may appear short on one exchange while holding spot assets or a long position elsewhere.

The ratio rarely captures the participant’s complete portfolio.

It should be treated as limited platform-specific information.

### Top-Trader Positioning

Some exchanges publish data for accounts classified as top traders.

This may include account ratios or position ratios.

The label does not guarantee that the traders are informed, profitable or taking outright directional views.

Professional participants may use derivatives for hedging.

A large short position may protect a larger spot holding.

Copying the visible direction without understanding the hedge can create the opposite economic exposure.

### Taker Buy and Sell Volume

Taker volume measures orders that immediately remove liquidity.

Taker buyers cross the spread to execute against asks.

Taker sellers execute against bids.

Persistent taker buying can indicate aggressive demand.

Persistent taker selling can indicate aggressive supply.

However, every transaction still includes both a buyer and seller.

The measure identifies which side demanded immediate execution.

It does not reveal the complete motive.

### Cumulative Volume Delta

Cumulative volume delta, often abbreviated CVD, tracks the difference between aggressive buying and selling over time.

A simplified calculation is:

CVD = Cumulative taker-buy volume − Cumulative taker-sell volume

If CVD rises, aggressive buying is dominating.

If it falls, aggressive selling is dominating.

CVD may be calculated separately for spot and derivatives markets.

This separation can help identify whether a move is led by real asset purchases or leveraged contracts.

### Price and CVD Divergence

Suppose price rises while derivatives CVD rises strongly but spot CVD remains weak.

The rally may be derivatives led.

Suppose price remains stable while spot CVD rises.

Buyers may be absorbing selling without yet pushing price higher.

Divergence can provide useful context.

It is not a guaranteed reversal signal.

Large passive sellers or buyers may absorb aggressive orders for an extended period.

### Absorption

Absorption occurs when substantial aggressive buying or selling fails to move price significantly.

For example, strong taker selling may occur near support, but price stops declining.

A large passive buyer may be absorbing the sell orders.

This can indicate potential stabilisation.

The opposite can occur near resistance, where aggressive buying is absorbed by a large seller.

Absorption is inferred from order flow and price response.

The visible participant may later withdraw, so the level remains vulnerable.

### Order-Book Liquidity and Liquidation Risk

A liquidation cascade becomes more severe when order-book depth is weak.

Forced market orders consume the available liquidity.

As each price level is exhausted, the market moves to the next.

Thin liquidity increases slippage and causes liquidations to execute at progressively worse prices.

This can create losses beyond traders’ planned liquidation estimates and place pressure on exchange insurance systems.

### Insurance Funds and Automatic Deleveraging

When liquidated positions cannot be closed without creating a deficit, exchanges may use insurance funds.

If those funds are insufficient, automatic deleveraging may reduce profitable opposing positions.

A trader may therefore be closed involuntarily even when their analysis was correct.

The probability is generally low on well-capitalised venues under ordinary conditions.

It can rise during extreme market events.

Derivatives analysis should include platform structure, not only price data.

### Options Positioning

Derivatives positioning extends beyond futures and perpetuals.

Options open interest can reveal where large call and put positions are concentrated.

Analysts may examine:

Strike-level open interest

Put-call ratios

Expiry concentration

Implied volatility skew

Dealer gamma exposure

Options data can influence price behaviour near major expiries.

However, the direction of the effect depends on who owns and who sold the options, how positions are hedged and whether contracts are exercised or closed.

Open interest at a strike does not reveal the complete market exposure.

### Put-Call Ratios

A put-call ratio compares put activity with call activity.

It may use volume or open interest.

A high ratio can indicate strong demand for puts, which may reflect bearish speculation or protective hedging.

A low ratio may indicate greater call demand and bullish speculation.

The interpretation is ambiguous because:

Put buyers may be hedging long portfolios

Put sellers may be bullish

Call sellers may be neutral or bearish

Call buyers may be speculative

The ratio measures contract activity, not pure sentiment.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',5,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
