INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-11-lesson-02','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Transactions and UTXO and Account-Based Models','cmf-module-3-11','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Transactions and UTXO and Account-Based Models, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Transactions

A transaction is an instruction submitted to the blockchain.

It may transfer an asset, interact with a smart contract, delegate stake or perform another function permitted by the network.

A transaction normally includes a unique identifier known as a transaction hash.

The record may also show:

Block number

Timestamp

Sender

Recipient

Amount

Fee

Confirmation status

Input data

On smart contract networks, one user transaction can generate several internal actions.

For example, a decentralised exchange swap may involve transfers between the user, a router contract and one or more liquidity pools.

Counting only the outer transaction may fail to capture the complete economic activity.

### Addresses, Wallets and Entities

These terms are often used interchangeably, but they are not identical.

An address is a blockchain destination associated with cryptographic control.

A wallet is software or hardware used to manage keys and interact with one or more addresses.

An entity is the person, company, protocol, exchange or organisation believed to control an address or group of addresses.

One wallet application may create many addresses.

One exchange may control thousands or millions of addresses.

One person may use several wallets, exchanges and blockchain networks.

For this reason, a count of addresses is not the same as a count of users.

### Address Clustering

Address clustering is the process of grouping addresses that may be controlled by the same entity.

On Bitcoin, analysts may use transaction structure and spending behaviour to identify possible relationships between addresses.

On account-based networks, analysts may examine funding sources, repeated interaction patterns and known labels.

Clustering can improve the interpretation of blockchain activity.

For example, a transfer between two addresses owned by the same exchange should not necessarily be interpreted as a customer deposit or withdrawal.

Clustering is probabilistic.

Incorrect clustering can cause misleading conclusions about ownership, flows and concentration.

### Entity Labelling

Analytics providers may label addresses associated with known entities such as:

Exchanges

Custodians

Mining pools

Validators

Protocol treasuries

Bridges

Stablecoin issuers

Investment funds

Fraudulent schemes

Labels may come from public disclosures, transaction patterns, test deposits or other investigative methods.

A label can be outdated or incomplete.

An exchange may change its wallet structure. A protocol may migrate contracts. An address may serve more than one purpose.

Entity labels should therefore be treated as maintained datasets rather than permanent blockchain facts.

### Raw Data and Derived Metrics

Raw blockchain data consists of the original transactions, blocks and contract states.

Derived metrics transform that data into more understandable indicators.

Examples include:

Daily active addresses

Exchange inflows

Average transaction value

Realised capitalisation

Holder age distribution

Network-value ratios

Supply in profit

Staking participation

Every derived metric depends on a methodology.

The methodology determines:

Which transactions are counted

Which addresses are excluded

How entities are clustered

Which time period is used

How token movements are valued

How contract activity is interpreted

Two analytics platforms may publish different values for the same named metric because they use different methods.

### Data Cleaning

Blockchain activity contains noise.

A network may record:

Exchange internal transfers

Spam transactions

Automated bots

Airdrop claims

Contract maintenance

Arbitrage

Wash activity

Token migrations

A raw transaction count can rise dramatically without indicating meaningful user adoption.

Data cleaning attempts to remove or classify activity that would otherwise distort the metric.

This process can improve accuracy but introduces judgement.

An analyst should ask not only what a metric shows, but also what the provider included or excluded.

### Network-Specific Interpretation

On-chain metrics cannot always be compared directly across blockchains.

A transaction on Bitcoin differs economically from a transaction on Ethereum or a high-throughput smart contract network.

One network may encourage users to combine several actions into one transaction.

Another may generate many small transactions because fees are low.

Some networks execute transactions through rollups or secondary layers and later submit aggregated data to a base chain.

Others may use different account, staking or fee structures.

A higher transaction count does not automatically mean greater economic activity or adoption.

Metrics must be interpreted within the architecture of the network.

### UTXO and Account-Based Models

Bitcoin uses an unspent transaction output, or UTXO, model.

A wallet does not simply contain one balance entry. It controls individual outputs created by earlier transactions.

When those outputs are spent, new outputs are created.

This structure allows analysts to study the age and movement of individual coin units.

Ethereum and many other networks use an account-based model.

Balances and contract states are updated directly within accounts.

The two models produce different analytical opportunities and require different methodologies.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',2,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-11-lesson-03','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Smart Contract Activity and Token Burns','cmf-module-3-11','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Smart Contract Activity and Token Burns, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Smart Contract Activity

On a programmable blockchain, a transaction may do far more than send tokens.

A user may:

Swap assets

Deposit collateral

Borrow funds

Provide liquidity

Stake tokens

Mint an NFT

Vote in governance

Bridge assets

On-chain analysis can therefore examine the use of individual applications and protocols.

However, smart contract activity must be interpreted carefully.

A high volume of transactions may be generated by arbitrage bots rather than unique users.

A rise in locked assets may result from higher token prices rather than new deposits.

The economic meaning behind the contract activity matters.

### Active Addresses

An active address is generally an address that participated in a transaction during a specified period.

Some metrics count senders.

Others count both senders and receivers.

Some attempt to remove exchange or contract addresses.

Active-address growth may suggest increasing network participation.

It may also result from:

One entity creating many addresses

Bot activity

Airdrops

Spam

Internal exchange movement

Address-management practices

Active addresses are a useful activity measure, but not a precise count of people.

### New Addresses

New-address metrics count addresses appearing on-chain for the first time.

A sustained rise may suggest new users or new applications.

It can also occur because existing users generate new addresses for privacy, custody or operational reasons.

On Bitcoin, good privacy practice may involve using a new address for each transaction.

A single user can therefore produce many new addresses.

The metric is more meaningful when combined with transaction value, retention and other indicators of genuine network engagement.

### Transaction Count

Transaction count measures the number of recorded transactions during a period.

An increase may indicate greater use.

Yet one high-value settlement transaction can have more economic significance than thousands of low-value automated transfers.

Transaction count should be evaluated alongside:

Transaction value

Fees

Active users

Contract type

Network capacity

Spam controls

A network can increase transaction count by lowering costs without necessarily increasing valuable economic activity.

### Transaction Volume

On-chain transaction volume attempts to measure the value transferred through the blockchain.

This may be reported in:

Native asset units

Stablecoin value

National-currency equivalent

Raw transfer volume can be inflated by assets moving repeatedly between related addresses.

Analytics providers may attempt to calculate adjusted transfer volume by excluding known internal or repetitive transfers.

The adjustment method matters.

A large transfer volume does not prove that the network generated equivalent economic value.

### Average and Median Transaction Value

Average transaction value is calculated by dividing total transfer value by transaction count.

It can be distorted by a small number of extremely large transactions.

Median transaction value identifies the middle transaction and may better reflect typical use.

Comparing average with median can reveal whether activity is dominated by large institutional transfers or many smaller transactions.

Neither measure identifies the purpose of the transfers.

### Network Fees

Network fees are payments made to miners, validators or other transaction processors.

Fee levels can reveal demand for limited block space.

Rising fees may indicate greater network usage.

They may also indicate congestion, speculation or inefficient network capacity.

High fees can benefit network security or token economics in some designs.

They can also make the network too expensive for ordinary users.

Fee analysis should therefore consider both demand and accessibility.

### Fee Revenue

For some networks, transaction fees represent revenue paid to validators, token holders or protocol participants.

Analysts may compare fee generation with:

Market capitalisation

Token issuance

Validator rewards

Application revenue

User activity

A network generating meaningful fees may demonstrate economic demand for its services.

High fees during one speculative event may not be sustainable.

The destination of those fees also matters.

They may be burned, distributed or retained by intermediaries.

### Issuance and Supply Changes

Blockchains may create new units through mining, staking rewards or other issuance mechanisms.

They may also destroy units through token burns or fee-burning systems.

On-chain analysis can track:

New issuance

Burned supply

Net supply growth

Staked or locked supply

Circulating supply

Supply change affects scarcity.

It does not determine price by itself.

Demand, liquidity and distribution remain essential.

### Token Burns

A token burn permanently removes units from usable supply, usually by sending them to an inaccessible address or reducing supply through contract logic.

Burns may occur automatically or through governance decisions.

A burn can reduce future supply.

Its economic importance depends on its size relative to:

Current circulation

New issuance

Token unlocks

Demand

A project can burn tokens while issuing even more elsewhere.

The relevant measure is net supply change.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',3,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-11-lesson-04','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Staking Data and Realised Price','cmf-module-3-11','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Staking Data and Realised Price, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Staking Data

Proof-of-stake networks allow holders to commit assets to network security.

On-chain data may show:

Total amount staked

Validator count

Validator concentration

Entry and exit queues

Staking rewards

Slashing events

A high staking rate can reduce liquid supply and indicate confidence in the network.

It can also create concentration, liquidity and governance risks.

Assets described as staked may still remain economically liquid through staking derivatives.

The headline staking percentage does not reveal the complete market impact.

### Holder Distribution

Holder-distribution analysis examines how token supply is divided among addresses or entities.

An asset may appear decentralised because it has many addresses while most supply is controlled by a small number of insiders, custodians or protocols.

Concentration can create risks including:

Market manipulation

Governance dominance

Sudden selling

Liquidity shocks

Large addresses may also represent exchanges holding assets for many customers.

Entity identification is therefore essential before describing one address as one whale.

### Whales

The term whale generally refers to an entity controlling a large asset position.

Analysts often monitor whale transfers because large holders may influence liquidity.

A large transfer can attract attention, but its meaning is uncertain.

It may represent:

Exchange deposit

Withdrawal

Custody migration

Collateral

Internal restructuring

Sale

Purchase

Over-the-counter settlement

A whale alert is evidence that assets moved.

It is not proof of an intended trade.

### Exchange Inflows

Exchange inflows measure assets transferred into addresses believed to belong to exchanges.

They are often interpreted as potential selling supply because holders may deposit assets to trade.

A large inflow can increase the probability of selling.

It can also represent:

Collateral deposit

Market-making inventory

Internal transfer

Derivative settlement

Custody service

The effect depends on the asset, exchange and broader market context.

A single large inflow should not automatically be treated as bearish.

### Exchange Outflows

Exchange outflows measure assets leaving recognised exchange addresses.

They are often interpreted as movement into self-custody and reduced immediate selling supply.

This may support a long-term accumulation thesis.

However, an outflow can also reflect:

Exchange wallet reorganisation

Institutional custody transfer

Collateral deployment

DeFi activity

Movement to another venue

Sustained net outflows combined with other evidence may be more informative than one transaction.

### Exchange Net Flow

Exchange net flow is commonly calculated as:

Inflows − Outflows

A positive net flow means more assets entered recognised exchange addresses than left.

A negative net flow means more left than entered.

The metric may be noisy because large internal wallet movements can dominate the result.

Analysts often use moving averages or longer periods to identify sustained trends.

### Exchange Balances

Exchange-balance metrics estimate how much supply is held in known exchange wallets.

A declining balance may suggest that more assets are moving into self-custody or long-term storage.

A rising balance may indicate greater readily tradable supply.

The interpretation depends on accurate exchange labels.

It may also be affected by changes in custody structure and the growth of exchange-traded investment products or institutional custodians.

### Holder Age

On UTXO-based networks, analysts can estimate how long individual units have remained unmoved.

Coins that have not moved for years may be classified as long-term holdings.

Recently moved coins may be associated with more active market participants.

Holder-age analysis can reveal changes in the behaviour of older and newer supply.

It does not identify the legal owner or guarantee that unmoved assets are intentionally held.

Some may be lost or inaccessible.

### Coin Days

A coin-day measure combines asset quantity with the length of time it remained unmoved.

One coin held for one day creates one coin day.

Ten coins held for one hundred days create one thousand coin days.

When older coins move, a larger number of coin days is destroyed.

This can indicate that long-dormant supply has become active.

A movement by old coins may represent selling, custody changes or other activity.

The destination and market context remain important.

### Long-Term and Short-Term Holders

Some analytical frameworks classify holders according to how long their assets have remained unmoved.

Long-term holders are generally considered less likely to sell in response to ordinary volatility.

Short-term holders may be more sensitive to price changes.

These classifications are statistical conventions rather than direct knowledge of investor intention.

A long-held coin can be sold suddenly.

A recently acquired coin may be intended for permanent storage.

### Realised Price

Realised price is an on-chain valuation concept.

Instead of valuing every coin at the current market price, it values units according to the price when they last moved on-chain.

The combined value is divided by circulating supply to estimate an average on-chain cost basis.

This differs from ordinary market price.

Realised price can provide insight into whether the average moved unit is currently in profit or loss.

Its meaning depends on the network and methodology.

Lost coins, exchange transfers and non-economic transactions can affect the result.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',4,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-11-lesson-05','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Realised Capitalisation and Metcalfe’s Law and Network Effects','cmf-module-3-11','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Realised Capitalisation and Metcalfe’s Law and Network Effects, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Realised Capitalisation

Realised capitalisation values each unit at the price at which it last moved, rather than at today’s price.

It may provide a different perspective on the capital stored in the network.

Market capitalisation can rise dramatically when the latest traded price increases, even if only a small amount of supply traded at that level.

Realised capitalisation changes when assets move at new prices.

It can therefore respond more slowly than market capitalisation.

This metric is especially associated with transparent UTXO networks.

### Market Value to Realised Value

Market Value to Realised Value, commonly called MVRV, compares market capitalisation with realised capitalisation.

A simplified formula is:

MVRV = Market capitalisation ÷ Realised capitalisation

A high ratio may indicate that holders collectively have large unrealised profits.

A low ratio may indicate that market value is close to or below the estimated aggregate cost basis.

Analysts sometimes use extreme historical values to study market cycles.

The metric does not guarantee a top or bottom.

Market structure, adoption and valuation regimes can change.

### Supply in Profit and Loss

On-chain models may estimate the proportion of supply held above or below its last-moved price.

A unit is considered in profit when the current market price exceeds the price at which it last moved.

It is considered in loss when current price is lower.

High supply in profit can create potential selling pressure because many holders can realise gains.

It can also occur throughout a strong bull market.

High supply in loss can signal stress, but losses may persist during prolonged bear markets.

### Realised Profit and Loss

Realised profit occurs when an asset moves at a higher market price than when it previously moved.

Realised loss occurs when it moves at a lower price.

Aggregating these movements can provide insight into whether participants are taking profit or capitulating.

Large realised profits may appear during strong rallies.

Large realised losses may occur during panic.

Not every transfer represents an actual sale, so these metrics rely on assumptions.

### Spent Output Profit Ratio

The Spent Output Profit Ratio, or SOPR, is an on-chain metric often used for UTXO assets.

It compares the price at which spent outputs are moved with the price at which they were previously created.

A value above one suggests that moved coins are, on average, being transferred at a profit.

A value below one suggests movement at a loss.

Values near one indicate movement near break-even.

SOPR may help analyse profit-taking and capitulation.

It does not confirm that every movement was a market sale.

### Dormancy

Dormancy uses the average age of moved coins or coin days destroyed relative to transaction volume.

A rise may indicate that older supply is becoming active.

A decline may suggest that transactions are dominated by recently moved coins.

Dormancy can help distinguish long-term holder movement from short-term circulation.

The metric can be distorted by large custody transfers involving old coins.

### HODL Waves

HODL waves group supply according to the length of time since units last moved.

They show how much supply has remained inactive for periods such as:

Less than one month

Several months

One year

Multiple years

The distribution can help analysts study long-term accumulation and spending.

The name is informal, but the underlying metric is based on holder age.

Growth in older bands may indicate that supply is maturing into longer-term holdings.

### Network Value Metrics

Analysts may compare network valuation with measures of activity.

One example is the Network Value to Transactions ratio.

A simplified form is:

Network value ÷ Transaction volume

The idea resembles comparing a company’s valuation with its economic throughput.

A high ratio may suggest that valuation is large relative to transaction activity.

A low ratio may suggest greater activity relative to value.

The metric is sensitive to how transaction volume is adjusted and whether transfers genuinely represent economic settlement.

### Network Value to Transactions Signal

Some frameworks smooth transaction volume to reduce noise and compare it with current network value.

This may produce a more stable signal than raw daily activity.

The methodology remains important.

Different smoothing periods and adjusted-volume calculations can create different conclusions.

No valuation ratio should be used as a standalone timing indicator.

### Metcalfe’s Law and Network Effects

Metcalfe’s Law proposes that the value of a network may grow approximately with the square of the number of connected users.

The concept is often applied to digital networks.

Blockchain analysts may compare asset value with active users or addresses.

The relationship is not exact.

Not all users contribute equal value, and one address is not necessarily one user.

The law is better understood as a general network-effect principle than a precise valuation formula.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',5,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
