INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-13-lesson-11','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Module Summary and Key Takeaway','cmf-module-3-13','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Module Summary and Key Takeaway, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Module Summary

Wallet and holder-cohort analysis organises blockchain assets into groups according to holding period, balance size, cost basis and spending behaviour.

The distinction between an address, wallet and economic entity is essential.

One entity can control many addresses, while one exchange or custodian address can represent assets belonging to millions of customers.

Holding-period analysis studies how long assets remain inactive.

Long-term holders are generally less active, while short-term holders may be more sensitive to recent price movement.

These are behavioural classifications rather than fixed investor identities.

Coin age, Coin Days Destroyed, dormancy, HODL waves and spent-volume age bands help identify whether current spending involves young or old supply.

Cost-basis metrics estimate the price at which assets last moved.

They can be calculated for long-term holders, short-term holders and other groups.

Price moving above or below a cohort cost basis may affect holder behaviour, but the level does not guarantee support or resistance.

Unrealised profit and loss describe the financial position of holders who have not yet moved their assets.

Realised profit, realised loss and SOPR estimate the economic result when assets move.

These metrics can provide evidence of profit-taking, distribution and capitulation.

Balance cohorts may show whether smaller or larger entities are accumulating.

They must be adjusted for exchanges, custodians, smart contracts, burn addresses, bridges and vesting contracts.

Accumulation and distribution are processes through which ownership transfers between cohorts.

Distribution can occur while price continues rising, and accumulation can occur while price continues falling.

Holder analysis is strongest when used to assess structural supply, market-cycle pressure and behavioural change.

It is weaker as a precise short-term timing tool.

A blockchain can reveal that old assets moved, that recent holders are under pressure or that supply is becoming concentrated.

It cannot reveal the full identity, motivation or off-chain position of every participant.

### Key Takeaway

Wallet behaviour can reveal how supply is moving between newer and older holders, profitable and unprofitable participants, and active and inactive entities.

It cannot reveal every investor’s identity or intention.

A large transfer is not automatically a sale. A dormant wallet is not guaranteed to remain dormant. An exchange address is not one whale.

Use holder cohorts to understand supply structure and behavioural pressure. Then require evidence from price, liquidity and market flows before turning that interpretation into a market decision.

The next module is 3.14: Exchange Inflows, Outflows and Reserve Analysis.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,3,0,0,0,'','',11,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
