INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-15-lesson-01','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Market Capitalisation and Realised Capitalisation','cmf-module-3-15','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Market Capitalisation and Realised Capitalisation, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Learning Objectives

By the end of this module, you should understand how realised capitalisation and realised price differ from ordinary market capitalisation and market price.

You should be able to explain how on-chain analysts estimate the cost basis of different parts of the circulating supply, including short-term holders, long-term holders and investors who acquired assets within particular price ranges.

You should also understand how realised profit, realised loss, supply in profit, MVRV and cost-basis distributions can contribute to market-cycle analysis.

Most importantly, you should recognise that on-chain cost basis is an estimate based on asset movement. It is not a verified record of what every investor paid, and it should not be treated as an objective calculation of fair value.

### Introduction

Market price tells us what a willing buyer and seller agreed upon in the most recent transaction.

Market capitalisation then applies that latest price to the entire circulating supply.

If a digital asset has one million circulating units and the latest market price is 100 units, its market capitalisation is:

1,000,000 × 100 = 100,000,000 units

This calculation is useful, but it contains an important simplification.

It assumes that every circulating unit can be valued at the latest market price, even though most units may not have moved anywhere near that price.

Some holders may have acquired their assets years earlier at much lower prices. Others may have entered recently near the current price. Some assets may belong to exchanges, custodians, protocols or inactive wallets.

On-chain analysis provides another way to examine network value.

Instead of valuing every unit at the current market price, realised-value frameworks attempt to value each unit according to the price at which it last moved on the blockchain.

This creates an estimated network-wide cost basis.

The resulting measures can help analysts explore questions such as:

Are holders collectively sitting on large unrealised profits?

Are recent buyers under pressure?

Has substantial new capital entered the network?

Are losses being realised at an unusual rate?

Is price trading above or below the estimated cost basis of an important holder cohort?

These measures can provide powerful market context.

They also rely on assumptions.

A coin moving between two wallets controlled by the same person does not represent a new purchase. An exchange withdrawal does not reveal the customer’s original acquisition price. A transfer to a staking contract can reset the last-moved price even though beneficial ownership remains unchanged.

Realised value should therefore be treated as an analytical model rather than a complete accounting record.

### Market Capitalisation

Market capitalisation is calculated by multiplying current market price by circulating supply.

The formula is:

Market capitalisation = Current price × Circulating supply

Suppose a cryptocurrency has a circulating supply of ten million tokens and trades at 20 units.

Its market capitalisation is:

10,000,000 × 20 = 200,000,000 units

Market capitalisation answers a useful question:

What would the circulating supply be worth if every unit were valued at the latest market price?

It does not mean that 200 million units of capital have entered the asset.

A relatively small amount of trading can move the market price, changing the quoted market capitalisation of the entire supply.

This distinction is important when interpreting rapid changes in asset value.

### The Limitations of Market Capitalisation

Market capitalisation is sensitive to the latest traded price.

Suppose a thinly traded token has one billion units in circulation. Only a small quantity trades at one unit per token.

The reported market capitalisation becomes one billion units, even though attempting to sell a large percentage of the supply would likely cause the price to fall sharply.

Market capitalisation therefore does not measure:

Cash invested directly into the asset

Capital available to support the current price

The amount holders could withdraw simultaneously

The average price paid by investors

Market liquidity

It remains a useful relative valuation measure, but it should not be confused with realised capital or immediately accessible value.

### Realised Capitalisation

Realised capitalisation values units according to the market price when they last moved on-chain.

Instead of applying today’s price to every unit, it assigns a different price to different portions of the supply.

Suppose a simplified network contains three coins:

Coin A last moved when market price was 10

Coin B last moved when market price was 30

Coin C last moved when market price was 50

Realised capitalisation is:

10 + 30 + 50 = 90 units

If the current market price is 100, market capitalisation is:

3 × 100 = 300 units

The difference reflects the fact that the coins entered their current on-chain positions at much lower market prices.

Realised capitalisation attempts to estimate the capital value stored in the network according to historical movement.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',1,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-15-lesson-02','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Realised Price and Entity-Adjusted Realised Value','cmf-module-3-15','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Realised Price and Entity-Adjusted Realised Value, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Realised Price

Realised price is calculated by dividing realised capitalisation by circulating supply.

The formula is:

Realised price = Realised capitalisation ÷ Circulating supply

Using the previous example:

90 ÷ 3 = 30 units

The realised price is thirty, while the current market price is one hundred.

This suggests that the average unit, valued at its last-moved price, has an estimated cost basis of thirty.

The metric is often interpreted as an aggregate on-chain cost basis.

It is not the verified average purchase price of every holder.

### Market Price Versus Realised Price

When market price is above realised price, the aggregate supply is estimated to hold unrealised profit.

When market price falls below realised price, the aggregate supply is estimated to hold unrealised loss.

This can have behavioural implications.

A market trading well above realised price may support confidence because many holders are profitable.

It may also create significant potential profit-taking.

A market trading below realised price may indicate broad financial stress.

Some holders may capitulate. Others may view the level as an attractive long-term opportunity.

The relationship does not determine what must happen next.

Price can remain above or below realised price for extended periods.

### Why Realised Capitalisation Changes

Market capitalisation changes whenever the market price changes.

Realised capitalisation changes mainly when assets move on-chain at prices different from their previous last-moved prices.

Suppose a coin last moved when price was 10 and moves again when price is 100.

Its contribution to realised capitalisation rises from 10 to 100.

This represents a ninety-unit increase in the network’s estimated realised value.

If a coin last moved at 100 and later moves at 60, its contribution falls from 100 to 60.

Realised capitalisation can therefore rise during periods when assets move at higher prices and decline when large amounts of supply move at losses.

### Realised Capital Inflows

An increase in realised capitalisation is often interpreted as capital entering the network or coins being repriced at higher cost bases.

During a bull market, new investors may purchase assets from earlier holders at higher prices.

As those assets move, their realised values increase.

This can indicate that the market is absorbing supply at progressively higher valuations.

However, not every increase represents a genuine purchase.

Internal transfers, exchange withdrawals and custody movements can also reprice assets within the model.

Entity-adjusted data can reduce some of this noise.

### Realised Capital Outflows

Realised capitalisation may decline when assets move at prices below their previous last-moved prices.

This can occur during bear markets and capitulation.

Recent buyers may sell at losses, resetting the cost basis of their assets to lower levels.

A decline in realised capitalisation can indicate that capital is being destroyed economically through loss realisation.

It does not mean physical currency is literally leaving the blockchain.

It means the market is accepting lower valuations for moved supply.

### Realised Value Is Not Cash Flow

A common misunderstanding is to treat realised capitalisation as the amount of money invested in the network.

The metric is not a direct sum of deposits or purchase payments.

It assigns a market price to each coin when that coin last moved.

A transaction between two self-controlled wallets can change the realised value without any purchase.

A trade completed inside a centralised exchange can change beneficial ownership without producing an immediate on-chain movement.

Realised capitalisation is therefore a valuation model based on blockchain movement, not a complete cash-flow statement.

### Cost-Basis Estimation

Cost basis is the price at which an investor effectively acquired an asset.

Blockchain data rarely provides this information directly.

Suppose a person buys Bitcoin on a centralised exchange at 40,000 and withdraws it two months later when market price is 50,000.

The blockchain sees the withdrawal at 50,000.

An on-chain model may assign the coins a cost basis near 50,000, even though the investor paid 40,000.

Similarly, an investor may transfer coins between personal wallets when price is 70,000, resetting the last-moved price without changing beneficial ownership.

The model remains useful at an aggregate level, but individual cost-basis estimates can be inaccurate.

### Entity-Adjusted Realised Value

Entity-adjusted methods attempt to identify transfers between addresses controlled by the same economic entity.

If a person moves assets from one personal wallet to another, the transfer may be excluded from cost-basis repricing.

If an exchange moves assets between cold wallets, the transfer may also be ignored.

This can improve the economic meaning of realised-value metrics.

The adjustment depends on address clustering.

Incorrect clustering can exclude genuine transfers or include internal movements.

Entity-adjusted data should be considered a refined estimate rather than an objective reconstruction of ownership.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',2,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
