INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-15-lesson-09','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Historical Thresholds and On-Chain Cost Basis and Position Sizing','cmf-module-3-15','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Historical Thresholds and On-Chain Cost Basis and Position Sizing, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Historical Thresholds

Analysts often identify historical MVRV, NUPL or realised-price levels associated with previous market tops and bottoms.

These observations can provide context.

They should not be treated as immutable thresholds.

The market can change through:

Greater institutional participation

New custody structures

Derivative growth

Regulatory changes

Reduced volatility

Different issuance schedules

A level that mattered in earlier cycles may behave differently in the future.

### Percentile Analysis

Instead of relying on fixed thresholds, an analyst may compare a metric with its historical percentile.

A reading in the ninety-fifth percentile is higher than approximately ninety-five percent of observations in the selected sample.

This provides relative context.

The result depends on the sample period.

Including only one market cycle can create misleading conclusions.

Historical percentiles also assume that the future resembles the past sufficiently for comparison.

### Z-Scores and Standardisation

A Z-score measures how far a metric is from its historical average in standard-deviation units.

The formula is:

Z-score = (Current value − Historical mean) ÷ Historical standard deviation

Standardisation helps compare periods with different market sizes.

Financial data frequently has fat tails and changing distributions.

A high Z-score does not mean further movement is impossible.

It means the current reading is unusual relative to the selected history.

### Long-Term Valuation Bands

Some analysts create valuation bands around realised price.

These may use multiples such as:

Market price equal to realised price

Market price two times realised price

Market price three times realised price

The bands can show how far market valuation has expanded above aggregate cost basis.

They are descriptive.

No economic law requires price to reverse at a particular multiple.

Bands should be compared with adoption, market regime and investor composition.

### Realised Price as a Valuation Floor

Realised price is sometimes described as a long-term valuation floor because price has historically spent limited time below it in certain assets.

The word “floor” can be misleading.

A floor implies that price cannot fall farther.

Markets can remain below realised price or establish much lower levels.

It is more accurate to describe realised price as an aggregate cost-basis reference associated with broad holder stress.

### Realised Price as Support

When price approaches realised price, some investors may view the market as attractively valued.

Existing holders may resist selling below aggregate basis.

This can support demand.

Support depends on confidence in the asset’s future.

If the network or market structure deteriorates severely, holders may accept losses and sell below realised price.

The metric has behavioural relevance, not physical force.

### Realised Price as Resistance

After price falls below realised price, a later recovery may encounter resistance.

Holders who endured unrealised losses may sell as the market returns toward estimated break-even.

If price reclaims and holds above realised price, this may suggest improving demand and profitability.

One brief move above the level is insufficient.

Market acceptance matters.

### Realised Value and Cycle Tops

Near later stages of a bull market, market capitalisation may expand far above realised capitalisation.

NUPL and MVRV rise as holders accumulate unrealised profit.

Long-term holders may begin realising gains.

This can create conditions associated with distribution and eventual cycle exhaustion.

These conditions can persist for a long time.

Attempting to short solely because MVRV is high can lead to large losses while the market continues appreciating.

### Realised Value and Cycle Bottoms

During deep declines, market price may approach or fall below realised price.

MVRV can fall toward or below one, while NUPL becomes low or negative.

Realised losses may surge as recent and eventually long-term holders capitulate.

These conditions can indicate historically depressed valuation and broad financial stress.

A durable bottom requires more than low valuation.

Selling must stabilise and new demand must emerge.

### Transitional Conditions

A transition out of a bear market may involve several developments.

Realised losses begin declining. Price recovers above an important cohort cost basis. Short-term holder MVRV moves above one and remains there. Realised capitalisation stabilises or begins growing.

These changes suggest that capital is entering at higher prices and recent holders are regaining profitability.

The evidence becomes stronger when price structure, spot demand and market liquidity improve.

No single transition metric confirms a new bull market.

### On-Chain Cost Basis and Position Sizing

Cost-basis metrics can contribute to trade planning, but they should not determine position size directly.

Position size should still depend on:

Maximum acceptable loss

Price invalidation

Volatility

Liquidity

Portfolio correlation

A historically low MVRV does not justify unlimited exposure.

The metric can remain low while price continues falling.

Valuation confidence should never replace risk control.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',9,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-15-lesson-10','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Building a Realised-Value Dashboard','cmf-module-3-15','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Building a Realised-Value Dashboard, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Building a Realised-Value Dashboard

A focused realised-value dashboard may include market price, realised price, short-term holder realised price and long-term holder realised price.

It may also include MVRV, NUPL, realised profit and loss, SOPR and cost-basis distribution.

The dashboard should not contain every possible derivative of the same data.

Many realised-value indicators are mathematically related.

Using several correlated metrics can create the false impression of independent confirmation.

The analyst should understand which measures add genuinely different information.

### Avoiding Metric Redundancy

Market price versus realised price, MVRV and NUPL all describe related aspects of the gap between current valuation and estimated cost basis.

A strategy using all three may appear to have three confirming signals.

In reality, they may be transformations of the same underlying relationship.

Independent confirmation should come from other evidence such as exchange flows, spot volume, derivatives positioning or network activity.

### Data Revisions

Realised-value data can change when providers improve entity labels, correct supply estimates or revise methodology.

Historical readings may be recalculated.

This does not mean the blockchain history changed.

The model’s interpretation changed.

Analysts should document data sources and avoid comparing series from different providers without checking consistency.

### A Practical Realised-Value Process

Begin by defining the question.

If the objective is to understand aggregate holder profitability, compare market price with realised price and examine MVRV or NUPL.

If the question concerns recent investor pressure, focus on short-term holder cost basis, short-term holder MVRV and SOPR.

If the objective is to identify potential support or overhead supply, examine cost-basis distribution.

Next, check whether the metric is entity adjusted and appropriate for the network.

Compare the current reading with several market regimes rather than one historical event.

Then integrate realised-value evidence with price structure, exchange flows, derivatives and fundamentals.

The final conclusion should explain both the likely behavioural pressure and the conditions that would invalidate it.

### Example: Price Above Short-Term Holder Cost Basis

Suppose market price rises above the short-term holder realised price after a prolonged decline.

Recent holders move back into estimated profit.

SOPR rises above one, while spot demand improves.

This may indicate that the market is absorbing supply at higher prices and that recent buyers are regaining confidence.

If price quickly falls back below the level on strong selling, the recovery thesis weakens.

### Example: Price Below Realised Price

Suppose market price falls below aggregate realised price.

MVRV moves below one and NUPL becomes negative.

Realised losses rise sharply.

These conditions indicate broad stress and historically depressed cost-basis valuation.

They do not prove that the asset is fundamentally sound or that the decline has ended.

A stronger reversal case would require stabilising realised losses, improving demand and recovery in market structure.

### Example: Cost-Basis Resistance

Suppose a large amount of supply last moved between 40 and 45.

Price falls to 25 and later recovers.

As price approaches 40, exchange inflows increase from addresses associated with that cohort.

The recovery stalls.

This supports the interpretation that holders are selling near break-even.

A decisive move above 45 on strong spot demand would indicate that the overhead supply has been absorbed.

### Example: Realised Capitalisation Growth Without Price Growth

Suppose price trades sideways for six months.

Realised capitalisation rises steadily as old low-cost supply changes hands near the current price.

This indicates that supply is being repriced upward and capital is being absorbed.

The pattern could represent accumulation by new long-term holders or distribution from older holders.

Holder-age behaviour and the later range breakout help distinguish the two.

### Example: Misleading Token Realised Value

Suppose a project unlocks a large founder allocation.

The tokens move from a vesting contract to a founder wallet when market price is high.

A simple model assigns the entire allocation a high cost basis.

The founder may have paid almost nothing for the tokens.

The calculated realised capitalisation rises even though no new investment entered.

Token-specific realised-value metrics must account for non-market transfers and original allocation structures.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,5,0,0,0,'','',10,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-15-lesson-11','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Realised-Value Checklist and Common Misunderstandings','cmf-module-3-15','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Realised-Value Checklist and Common Misunderstandings, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Realised-Value Checklist

Before relying on a realised-value metric, ask:

Is the asset suited to last-moved-price analysis?

Is the blockchain UTXO based or account based?

Is the metric entity adjusted?

Are internal transfers and change outputs excluded?

How are exchange and custodian wallets treated?

Could dormant or lost supply distort realised price?

Are DeFi, bridge or staking transfers resetting cost basis without changing ownership?

Is the metric measuring aggregate supply or a specific holder cohort?

How is that cohort defined?

Is last-moved price a reasonable proxy for acquisition price?

Is the current reading unusual relative to several historical regimes?

Are fixed thresholds being treated too rigidly?

Is the metric mathematically redundant with other indicators in the analysis?

What does the metric suggest about unrealised profit or loss?

Is supply actually moving, or are gains and losses still unrealised?

What do realised profit and realised loss show?

Are exchange flows confirming distribution or capitulation?

What is derivatives positioning showing?

Does price structure support the cost-basis interpretation?

Have the network’s fundamentals or market structure changed?

What alternative explanation challenges the preferred conclusion?

What evidence would invalidate the thesis?

### Common Realised-Value Mistakes

A frequent mistake is describing realised price as the exact average purchase price of all investors. It is an estimate based on when assets last moved on-chain.

Another error is treating market price below realised price as proof that an asset is undervalued. The market may be repricing genuine fundamental deterioration.

Analysts may use MVRV, NUPL and market-price-to-realised-price relationships as if they were independent signals, even though they are closely related.

A further mistake is applying Bitcoin-based realised-value methods directly to tokens with vesting contracts, bridge assets and complex smart contract activity.

Some analysts treat every movement at a higher price as new capital entering. Self-transfers and custody migrations can also raise realised capitalisation.

Another error is using historical MVRV thresholds as guaranteed future tops or bottoms.

Finally, low valuation metrics are sometimes used to justify oversized positions. A statistically unusual reading can become more unusual before the market recovers.

### Common Misunderstandings

#### “Realised Capitalisation Measures the Exact Amount Invested”

It estimates supply value using last-moved prices and does not capture every off-chain purchase or internal transfer correctly.

#### “Realised Price Is the True Fair Value”

It is an estimated aggregate cost basis, not an intrinsic valuation.

#### “Price Below Realised Price Means the Market Must Recover”

Price can remain below aggregate cost basis or continue falling.

#### “MVRV Below One Guarantees a Bottom”

It indicates market value below realised value, not the end of selling.

#### “High MVRV Guarantees a Top”

Strong markets can remain highly profitable for extended periods.

#### “Supply in Profit Measures the Percentage of Profitable Investors”

It measures supply units according to estimated last-moved prices.

#### “Realised Profit Means Coins Were Sold for Cash”

It means assets moved at a higher market price than their previous on-chain basis.

#### “SOPR Above One Is Always Bullish”

It shows profit realisation. Excessive distribution can also weaken a market.

#### “A Cost-Basis Cluster Must Act as Support”

It may become resistance or accelerate selling after failure.

#### “Last-Moved Price Equals the Holder’s Entry Price”

Exchange purchases, self-transfers and custody movements can create differences.

#### “All Realised-Value Metrics Provide Independent Confirmation”

Many are derived from the same market-value and cost-basis relationship.

#### “A Historically Rare Reading Is Impossible to Exceed”

Market regimes and distributions change.

#### “Realised-Value Analysis Replaces Fundamental Analysis”

Historical cost basis cannot determine whether the network’s future value remains intact.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,5,0,0,0,'','',11,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
