INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-26-lesson-03','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Multisignature Versus MPC and Human Verification','cmf-module-3-26','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Multisignature Versus MPC and Human Verification, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Multisignature Versus MPC

Multisignature and MPC both attempt to prevent one key or person from controlling assets.

Multisignature rules are often visible on-chain. The blockchain verifies that the required number of keys signed.

MPC generally produces one standard signature after an off-chain distributed process.

This can make the wallet appear like an ordinary single-signature address.

Neither approach is universally superior.

The choice depends on blockchain support, operational needs, transparency, recovery and provider dependence.

### Key Generation

Keys should be created in a secure and verifiable environment.

A weak random-number generator can produce predictable keys.

A compromised device can record them during creation.

Institutional key ceremonies often involve several witnesses, controlled hardware and documented procedures.

The purpose is to demonstrate that no unauthorised party obtained the key and that required backups were created correctly.

The key-generation process is part of the custody control environment.

### Key Ceremonies

A key ceremony is a formal process for creating, distributing or activating cryptographic keys.

Participants may verify devices, software versions, random generation and storage media.

Every step may be recorded and witnessed.

This can create an audit trail and reduce reliance on one person.

A ceremony that looks impressive but uses compromised equipment remains unsafe.

Procedural formality should support technical security rather than replace it.

### Key Backups

Key backups allow recovery after device failure, loss or destruction.

Backups create additional copies of sensitive material and therefore additional attack surfaces.

They should be protected through geographic separation, physical security and access controls.

A backup that has never been tested may fail when needed.

A backup accessed too easily can undermine the security of the primary system.

Recovery and theft prevention must be balanced.

### Recovery Procedures

Recovery procedures explain how the institution restores access when a signer, device or location becomes unavailable.

A good procedure should address:

Lost or damaged devices

Unavailable employees

Natural disaster

Cyberattack

Death or incapacity

Custodian failure

The process should be tested without exposing the full key.

Recovery cannot depend entirely on the person or system whose loss created the emergency.

### Key Rotation

Key rotation replaces an existing key or signer with a new one.

It may be required after staff changes, suspected compromise or scheduled security reviews.

Rotation is itself a sensitive transaction.

The institution must verify that the new key is secure and that the old key loses authority.

Delayed signer removal can leave former employees or compromised systems capable of approving transactions.

### Separation of Duties

Separation of duties prevents one person from initiating, approving and executing the same transaction.

One employee may prepare the request. Another verifies the destination and business purpose. Additional authorised parties approve the signature.

This reduces internal fraud and error.

The control is weakened when approvers simply confirm requests without independent review.

Separation must be practical, documented and enforced by systems rather than informal expectation alone.

### Transaction Approval Policies

Institutional custody platforms can enforce transaction policies.

Examples include:

Approval thresholds

Daily transfer limits

Approved destination addresses

Time delays

Geographic restrictions

Transaction-size escalation

A routine small payment may require two approvals.

A large transfer may require executive and compliance review.

Policy-based controls reduce the risk that one compromised account can move all assets immediately.

### Address Whitelisting

Whitelisting restricts withdrawals to approved blockchain addresses.

Adding a new address may require enhanced approval and a waiting period.

This protects against an attacker replacing the destination at the last moment.

Whitelisting creates operational delay.

It can be dangerous if the institution needs to move funds urgently to an unapproved address during a crisis.

Emergency exceptions should be carefully controlled.

### Transaction Simulation

Transaction simulation predicts what a blockchain transaction will do before it is signed.

It can identify token transfers, contract calls, permission changes and expected fees.

Simulation is especially valuable when interacting with smart contracts.

It can fail when state changes before execution or when the simulation system does not model every contract behaviour correctly.

Simulation supports informed approval. It does not replace contract and counterparty due diligence.

### Human Verification

Approvers should verify the network, asset, amount, destination and business purpose.

The address shown on one computer should be compared with an independently verified source.

Malware can alter copied addresses.

A familiar-looking prefix and suffix do not guarantee that the full address is correct.

Large transactions may justify a voice confirmation or other out-of-band procedure with the intended recipient.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',3,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-3-26-lesson-04','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Insider Risk and Delivery Versus Payment','cmf-module-3-26','text','## Your outcome

Explain the key ideas in Insider Risk and Delivery Versus Payment, distinguish evidence from assumption, and apply them to a practical digital-asset decision.

### Insider Risk

Employees, executives, contractors or service providers may misuse legitimate access.

An insider may collude with another approver, alter accounting records or introduce malicious software.

Technical security focused only on external attackers is incomplete.

Institutions need background checks, access reviews, logging, leave policies and incident reporting.

No one should retain access merely because they were trusted historically.

### Privileged Access Management

Privileged accounts can change security settings, approve transactions or access sensitive systems.

Their use should be tightly controlled and recorded.

Administrative access may require stronger authentication, temporary elevation and independent approval.

Dormant privileged accounts should be removed.

A compromised administrator can bypass controls that protect ordinary users.

### Cybersecurity Risk

Custodians and exchanges are attractive targets because one successful attack can expose large asset pools.

Threats include phishing, malware, supply-chain compromise, credential theft and denial-of-service attacks.

Cybersecurity should cover endpoints, internal networks, cloud infrastructure, software development and third-party providers.

Blockchain immutability can make fraudulent transfers difficult to reverse.

Prevention and rapid detection are therefore particularly important.

### Social Engineering

Attackers often target people rather than cryptography.

They may impersonate executives, clients, technology providers or regulators.

A message may claim that an urgent transfer is required.

Time pressure is used to bypass ordinary controls.

Staff should be trained to verify unusual instructions independently.

An emergency should increase verification rather than reduce it.

### Supply-Chain Risk

An institution depends on software libraries, hardware devices, cloud providers and security vendors.

A compromised update or external service can create access to custody systems.

The direct custodian may follow strong controls while one vendor introduces a vulnerability.

Third-party access should be limited and monitored.

Critical dependencies should have replacement and continuity plans.

### Business Continuity

Business-continuity planning ensures that essential operations can continue after disruption.

Possible events include:

Cyberattack

Power failure

Natural disaster

Staff unavailability

Network outage

Custodian interruption

The organisation should identify which functions must continue, how quickly they must recover and which alternative facilities are available.

Digital asset markets trade continuously.

A disruption occurring outside local business hours can still create immediate financial risk.

### Disaster Recovery

Disaster recovery focuses on restoring systems, data and access after failure.

Backups should include more than private keys.

Transaction records, accounting data, approval policies and client entitlements may also be critical.

Recovery procedures should be tested regularly.

A written plan that has never been exercised provides limited assurance.

The institution should know how long restoration realistically requires.

### Operational Resilience

Operational resilience is the ability to continue providing important services during disruption.

The objective is not to prevent every failure.

It is to limit the effect on clients and markets.

A resilient custodian may continue processing essential withdrawals while non-critical services remain unavailable.

Resilience requires redundancy, incident management, communication and tested recovery.

### Blockchain Network Risk

A custodian may operate correctly while the underlying blockchain becomes congested, reorganised or temporarily unavailable.

Transactions may remain pending.

Fees may rise sharply.

A network upgrade can change transaction formats or operational requirements.

Custody providers must monitor each supported network and maintain compatible infrastructure.

Supporting many assets increases operational complexity.

### Node Infrastructure

Custodians and exchanges rely on blockchain nodes to observe balances and broadcast transactions.

A faulty or compromised node can present incorrect information or delay transfers.

Institutions may operate their own nodes, use external providers or combine several sources.

Independent verification reduces dependence on one provider.

Node availability is part of transaction and reconciliation infrastructure.

### Blockchain Confirmations

A custodian must decide how many confirmations are required before crediting a deposit.

Too few confirmations create reorganisation and double-spend risk.

Too many create settlement delay.

The requirement may vary according to the blockchain, transaction size and network conditions.

A large deposit may justify a more conservative confirmation threshold than a routine retail transfer.

### Settlement

Settlement is the completion of an asset transfer and the fulfilment of the corresponding financial obligation.

In a spot trade, one party delivers the digital asset and the other delivers payment.

When both occur simultaneously, principal risk is reduced.

In fragmented markets, the asset and payment may move through separate systems at different times.

One party can deliver while the other fails.

This is settlement risk.

### Delivery Versus Payment

Delivery-versus-payment systems attempt to ensure that securities or digital assets move only when payment occurs.

Blockchain smart contracts can support atomic exchange when both assets exist within compatible systems.

Many institutional trades still involve bank money, custodians and separate ledgers.

True atomic settlement may not be possible across these systems.

Operational controls and trusted intermediaries remain necessary.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'','',4,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
